{"title_page": "Peter Piot", "text_new": "{{Infobox scientist\n| honorific-prefix = Baron\n|name              = Peter Piot\n|image             = Baron_Peter_Piot.jpg\n|image_size        = 150px\n|caption           = Peter Piot\n|birth_date        = {{Birth date and age|1949|2|17|df=y}}\n|birth_place       = [[Leuven]], [[Belgium]]\n|death_date        = \n|death_place       = \n|residence         = \n|citizenship       = \n|nationality       = [[Belgium|Belgian]]\n|ethnicity         = \n|field             = \n|work_institutions = [[London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine]]<br>{{nowrap|[[Institute of Tropical Medicine Antwerp]]}}<br>[[Imperial College London]]\n|alma_mater        = [[Ghent University]]<br>[[University of Antwerp]]\n|doctoral_advisor  = \n|doctoral_students = \n|known_for         = \n|author_abbrev_bot = \n|author_abbrev_zoo = \n|influences        = \n|influenced        = \n|prizes            = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Calderone Award]] {{small|(2003)}}\n* [[Vlerick Award]] {{small|(2004)}}\n* Flanders-America Award {{small|(2008)}}\n* Prince Mahidol Award {{small|(2013)}}\n* Prix International de l\u2019INSERM {{small|(2015)}}\n* [[John Dirks Canada Gairdner Global Health Award]] {{small|(2015)}}\n* [[Manson Medal]] {{small|(2016)}}}}\n|website          = {{URL|http://www.lshtm.ac.uk/aboutus/people/piot.peter}}\n|footnotes         = \n}}\n'''Peter Karel, Baron Piot''', [[Order of St Michael and St George|KCMG]], [[Royal College of Physicians|FRCP]], [[Academy of Medical Sciences|FMedSci]] (born 17 February 1949) is a [[Belgium|Belgian]] microbiologist known for his research into [[Ebola]] and [[AIDS]]. After helping discover the Ebola virus in 1976 and leading efforts to contain the first-ever recorded Ebola epidemic that same year, Piot became a pioneering researcher into AIDS. He has held key positions in the [[United Nations]] and [[World Health Organization]] involving AIDS research and management. He has also served as a professor at several universities worldwide.<ref>{{cite book |last=Piot |first=P. |title=No Time to Lose: A Life in Pursuit of Deadly Viruses |location= |publisher=W. W. Norton |year=2012 |isbn= }}</ref> He is the author of 16 books and over 550 scientific articles.\n\n==Early life and education==\nPiot was born in [[Leuven]], [[Belgium]]. He studied medicine at [[Ghent University]], and earned an [[Doctor of Medicine|M.D.]] in 1974. He then began working at the [[Institute of Tropical Medicine Antwerp]] while pursuing a graduate degree in clinical [[microbiology]] from the [[University of Antwerp]]. He received a [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] in microbiology from the University of Antwerp in 1980.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lshtm.ac.uk/aboutus/people/piot.peter|title=Peter Piot|website=LSHTM|language=en|access-date=2017-07-27}}</ref>\n\nPiot is fluent in [[English language|English]], [[French language|French]], and [[Dutch language|Dutch]].<ref name=background/>\n\n==Career==\nIn 1976, while working at the Institute of Tropical Medicine, Piot was part of a team that discovered the [[Ebola]] virus in a sample of blood taken from a sick nun working in [[Zaire]].<ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(77)92002-5| title = Isolation of Marburg-Like Virus from a Case of H\u00e6morrhagic Fever in Zaire| journal = The Lancet| volume = 309| issue = 8011| pages = 573\u2013574| year = 1977| last1 = Pattyn | first1 = S.| last2 = Groen | first2 = G. V. | last3 = Jacob | first3 = W.| last4 = Piot | first4 = P.| last5 = Courteille | first5 = G. | pmid=65663}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1038/35073639| pmid = 11309626| title = The global impact of HIV/AIDS| journal = Nature| volume = 410| issue = 6831| pages = 968\u201373| year = 2001| last1 = Piot | first1 = P. | last2 = Bartos | first2 = M. | last3 = Ghys | first3 = P. D. | last4 = Walker | first4 = N. | last5 = Schwartl\u00e4nder | first5 = B. | bibcode = 2001Natur.410..968P}}</ref> Piot and his colleagues subsequently traveled to Zaire to help quell the outbreak. Piot's team made key discoveries into how the virus spread, and traveled from village to village, spreading information and putting the ill and those who had come into contact with them into quarantine. The epidemic was stopped in three months, after it had killed almost 300 people.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/magazine-28262541 The virus detective who discovered Ebola in 1976]</ref> The events were dramatised<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b04v5fjr |title= Ebola |publisher=[[BBC]]}}</ref> by [[Mike Walker (radio dramatist)|Mike Walker]] on [[BBC Radio 4]] in December 2014 in a production by [[David Morley (writer)|David Morley]]. Piot narrated the programme.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b04v5fjr|title=Ebola, Afternoon Drama - BBC Radio 4|website=BBC|access-date=2017-07-27}}</ref>\n\nPiot has received the majority of the credit for discovering Ebola, since in 1976, he was the one to receive blood samples while working in a lab at the Institute for Tropical Medicine in Antwerp, Belgium.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.lshtm.ac.uk/aboutus/people/piot.peter |title = Peter Piot}}</ref> The samples were originally sent by Dr. [[Jean-Jacques Muyembe-Tamfum]], a Congolese doctor who obtained the blood samples from those sickened with a mysterious disease in then-Zaire, later discovered to be Ebola. In 2012, Piot published a memoir entitled ''No Time to Lose'' which chronicles his professional work, including the discovery of the Ebolavirus; he mentions Muyembe in passing rather than as a co-discoverer. Piot stated in 2019 that \"my book was not an attempt to write the history of Ebola, but more my personal experience\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2019/11/04/774863495/this-congolese-doctor-discovered-ebola-but-never-got-credit-for-it-until-now |title=This Congolese Doctor Discovered Ebola But Never Got Credit For It \u2014 Until Now |author=Eyder Peralta |publisher=NPR |date=November 4, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn the 1980s, Piot participated in a series of collaborative projects in Burundi, C\u00f4te d'Ivoire, Kenya, Tanzania, and Zaire. Project SIDA in Kinshasa, Zaire was the first international project on [[AIDS]] in Africa and is widely acknowledged as having provided the foundations of science's understanding of [[HIV]] infection in Africa. He was a professor of [[microbiology]], and of [[public health]] at the [[Prince Leopold Institute of Tropical Medicine]], in [[Antwerp]], and at the [[University of Nairobi]], [[Vrije Universiteit Brussel]], the [[University of Lausanne|Lausanne]], and a visiting professor at the [[London School of Economics]]. He was also a Senior Fellow at the [[University of Washington]] in Seattle, a Scholar in Residence at the [[Ford Foundation]], and a Senior Fellow at the [[Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation]].<ref name=background/>\n\nFrom 1991 to 1994, Piot was president of the [[International AIDS Society]]. In 1992, he became Assistant Director of the [[World Health Organization]]'s ''Global Programme on HIV/AIDS''. On 12 December 1994, he was appointed Executive Director of the ''[[Joint United Nations Programme on HIV/AIDS]]'' (UNAIDS) and Assistant-Secretary-General of the United Nations.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(08)60820-X| title = Peter Piot| journal = The Lancet| volume = 371| issue = 9628| pages = 1907| year = 2008| last1 = Shetty | first1 = P.| pmid=18539213}}</ref> \n\nFrom 2009 to 2010, Piot served as director of the Institute for Global Health at [[Imperial College London]].<ref name=background>[http://www.lshtm.ac.uk/aboutus/people/piot.peter Professor Peter Piot]</ref> \n\n===London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine===\nIn September 2010,{{citation needed|date=May 2017}} Piot became the director of the [[London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.lshtm.ac.uk/aboutus/introducing/welcome-director |title=Welcome from the Director |publisher=[[London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine]] |accessdate=6 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to his work at LSHTM, Piot is a member of the [[Institute of Medicine]] of the [[United States National Academy of Sciences|National Academy of Sciences of the United States]] and the Royal Academy of Medicine of Belgium, a Fellow of the [[Royal College of Physicians of London]], UK and a Fellow of the [[Academy of Medical Sciences]]. In 2011, [[Amy Gutmann]] appointed him to serve on the International Research Panel at the [[Presidential Commission for the Study of Bioethical Issues]]. \n\nIn 2014, in the face of an unprecedented [[2014 West Africa Ebola outbreak|Ebola epidemic in western Africa]], Piot and other scientists called for the emergency release of the experimental [[ZMapp]] vaccine for use on humans before it had undergone clinical testing on humans.<ref>{{cite web|date=6 August 2014 |url=http://www.latimes.com/world/africa/la-fg-three-ebola-experts-release-drugs-20140806-story.html|title=Three leading Ebola experts call for release of experimental drug|work=Los Angeles Times}}</ref> That year, he was appointed by Director General [[Margaret Chan]] to the [[World Health Organization]]'s Advisory Group on the Ebola Virus Disease Response, co-chaired by [[Sam Zaramba]] and [[David L. Heymann]].<ref>[https://www.who.int/csr/disease/ebola/advisory-groups/members/en/ Members of the WHO Advisory Group on the Ebola Virus Disease Response] [[World Health Organization]].</ref> He also chaired an independent panel convened by Harvard Global Health Institute and the London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine into the national and international response to the epidemic, which sharply criticised the response of the WHO and put forward ten recommendations for the body's reorganisation.<ref>{{citation|url= |title=Will Ebola change the game? Ten essential reforms before the next pandemic. The report of the Harvard-LSHTM Independent Panel on the Global Response to Ebola |author=Moon S |journal=Lancet |volume=386 |issue=10009 |pages=2204\u20132221 |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(15)00946-0|display-authors=etal |pmid=26615326|year=2015 }}</ref> In February 2020, he criticised the delay in declaring the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2019\u201320 novel coronavirus outbreak]] focused on [[Hubei]], China, a [[Public Health Emergency of International Concern]], and advocated a five-point scale for outbreaks, rather the current binary (emergency/no emergency) system.<ref>{{cite podcast |url=https://anchor.fm/lshtm/episodes/S1E5-Coronavirus---will-it-become-a-pandemic-eamji1 |title=Coronavirus - will it become a pandemic? (''LSHTM Viral'' S1E5) |time=06:34\u201307:56 |host=Peter Piot, James Barr |publisher=[[London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine]] |date=February 7, 2020 |accessdate=February 9, 2010  }}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, Piot was appointed to the [[European Commission]]\u2019s advisory panel on [[COVID-19]], co-chaired by [[Ursula von der Leyen]] and [[Stella Kyriakides]].<ref>[https://ec.europa.eu/commission/presscorner/detail/en/ip_20_481 COVID-19: Commission launches European team of scientific experts to strengthen EU coordination and medical response] [[European Commission]], press release of March 17, 2020.</ref>\n\n==Other activities==\n===Non-profit organizations===\n* [[Coalition for Epidemic Preparedness Innovations]] (CEPI), Member of the Board (since 2018)<ref>[https://cepi.net/about/whoweare/ Board] [[Coalition for Epidemic Preparedness Innovations]] (CEPI).</ref><ref>[https://cepi.net/news_cepi/cepi-announces-new-permanent-board/ CEPI announces new permanent board] [[Coalition for Epidemic Preparedness Innovations]] (CEPI), press release of January 24, 2018.</ref>\n* Africa Health Research Institute (AHRI), Chair of the Board of Directors (since 2017)<ref>[https://www.ahri.org/structure-governance/ Governance] Africa Health Research Institute (AHRI).</ref>[https://www.ahri.org/olive-shisana-peter-piot-appointed-africa-health-research-institute-board/ Olive Shisana and Peter Piot appointed to Africa Health Research Institute Board] Africa Health Research Institute (AHRI), press release of January 31, 2017.</ref>\n* UK Collaborative on Development Research (UKCDR), Chair of the Strategic Coherence of ODA-funded Research (since 2017)<ref>[https://www.ukcdr.org.uk/about-us/our-governance/ Strategic Coherence of ODA-funded Research] UK Collaborative on Development Research (UKCDR).</ref><ref>[https://www.ukcdr.org.uk/news-article/announcing-the-chair-of-the-new-hmg-scor-board/ Announcing the Chair of the new HMG SCOR Board] UK Collaborative on Development Research (UKCDR), press release of September 26, 2017.</ref>\n* Africa Research Excellence Fund (AREF), Member of the Advisory Panel (since 2015)<ref>[http://www.africaresearchexcellencefund.org.uk/about-us/our-governance/our-advisory-panel/ Advisory Panel] Africa Research Excellence Fund (AREF).</ref>\n* [[Novartis Foundation]], Member of the Board of Trustees (since 2015)<ref>[https://www.novartisfoundation.org/about-us/board-trustees Board of Trustees] [[Novartis Foundation]].</ref><ref>[https://www.novartis.com/news/media-releases/novartis-foundation-confirms-new-members-its-board-trustees-including-new-chairman-dr-joerg-reinhardt Novartis Foundation confirms new members of its Board of trustees, including new Chairman Dr. Joerg Reinhardt] [[Novartis Foundation]], press release of July 27, 2015.</ref>\n* [[Antwerp Management School]], Member of the International Advisory Board<ref>[https://www.antwerpmanagementschool.be/en/about/international-advisory-board International Advisory Board] [[Antwerp Management School]].</ref> \n* Centre Virchow-Villerm\u00e9, Member of the International Advisory Board<ref>[https://virchowvillerme.eu/international-advisory-board-2/ International Advisory Board] Centre Virchow-Villerm\u00e9.</ref>\n* [[Global Health Innovative Technology Fund (GHIT)|Global Health Innovative Technology Fund]] (GHIT), Member of the Board of Directors<ref>[https://www.ghitfund.org/leadership/boardofdirectors Board of Directors] Global Health Innovative Technology Fund (GHIT Fund).</ref>\n* [[University of Washington]], External Member of the Advisory Board at the Department of Global Health<ref>[https://globalhealth.washington.edu/peter-piot Peter Piot] [[University of Washington]].</ref>\n* [[World Health Summit]], Member of the Council<ref>[https://www.worldhealthsummit.org/about-whs/leadership.html Council] [[World Health Summit]].</ref>\n===Editorial boards===\n* ''[[The Lancet]]'', Member of the International Advisory Board<ref>[https://www.thelancet.com/lancet/international-advisory-board International Advisory Board] ''[[The Lancet]]''.</ref>\n* ''[[The Lancet|The Lancet Public Health]]'', Member of the Editorial Advisory Board (since 2016)<ref>[https://www.thelancet.com/lanpub/editorial-advisory-board Editorial Advisory Board] ''[[The Lancet]]''.</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\n===Awards===\n*[[Frank A. Calderone Prize in Public Health]] (2003)<ref name=\"Calderone\">{{cite web | title=Past Recipients | website=Columbia University Mailman School of Public Health | date=8 September 2018 | url=https://www.mailman.columbia.edu/public-health-now/events/distinguished-lectures/calderone-prize/past-recipients | access-date=17 October 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Vlerick Award]] (2004)\n* America-Flanders Award (2008)<ref name=\"Flanders\">{{cite web | trans-title=Flanders-America Awards for Peter Piot and Bruyneel/Armstrong duo| title=Flanders-America Awards voor Peter Piot en duo Bruyneel/Armstrong | website=Het Nieuwsblad Mobile | date=25 February 2009 | url=https://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/dmf26022009_007 | language=nl | access-date=17 October 2018}}</ref> \n* [[Hideyo Noguchi Africa Prize]] (2013),<ref name=\"Noguchi\">{{cite news | last=Osaki | first=Tomohiro | title=Belgian, Ugandan win Noguchi prize | newspaper=The Japan Times Online | date=2 June 2013 | url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2013/06/02/national/politics-diplomacy/belgian-ugandan-win-noguchi-prize/ | access-date=17 October 2018}}</ref> \n* Prince Mahidol Award (2013)<ref name=\"Mahidol\">{{cite journal | last=Holmes | first=David | title=2013 Prince Mahidol Award winners announced | journal=The Lancet | volume=382 | issue=9908 | year=2013 | issn=0140-6736 | doi=10.1016/s0140-6736(13)62349-1 | pmid=24325009 | page=1869}}</ref> \n* Prix International de l\u2019INSERM (2015)<ref name=\"INSERM\">{{cite web | author= histoire | title=Peter Piot, Prix International 2015 / Histoire de l'Inserm | website=Histoire de l'Inserm | url=https://histoire.inserm.fr/de-l-inh-a-l-inserm/les-prix-inserm/prix-2015/peter-piot-prix-international-2015 | language=fr | access-date=17 October 2018}}</ref> \n* [[Canada Gairdner Global Health Award]] (2015)<ref name=\"Dirks\">{{cite journal | last=Maurice | first=John | title=Peter Piot wins 2015 Canada Gairdner Global Health Award | journal=The Lancet | volume=385 | issue=9974 | year=2015 | issn=0140-6736 | doi=10.1016/s0140-6736(15)60610-9 | pmid=25819690 | page=1170}}</ref> \n* [[Manson Medal]] (2016)<ref name=\"Manson\">{{cite web | title=Previous medal winners | website=Royal Society of Tropical Medicine and Hygiene | date=6 August 2014 | url=https://rstmh.org/awards/previous-medal-winners | access-date=17 October 2018}}</ref> \n\n===Honours===\n* [[Image:UK Order St-Michael St-George ribbon.svg|Ruban|45px]] Honorary Knight Commander of the [[Order of St Michael and St George]] (2016) \n*[[File:JPN Kyokujitsu-sho 1Class BAR.svg|45px|ribbon bar]] Grand Cordon of the [[Order of the Rising Sun]] (2018)\n\nPiot was appointed an Officer of the Order of the Leopard of Zaire in 1976 for his work during the Ebola outbreak, and was also appointed an Officer of the Order of the Lion of Senegal. He was ennobled as a Baron by King [[Albert II of Belgium]], in 1995. In 2016, he was made an honorary Knight Commander of the [[Order of St Michael and St George]] in the United Kingdom.<ref>[https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/581724/2016_Honorary_awards_V4.pdf Honorary awards]</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* Peter Piot - Biography (UNAIDS.org): [http://data.unaids.org/pub/Biography/2007/0207peterpiotbiog_en.pdf English] | [http://data.unaids.org/pub/Biography/2007/0207peterpiotbiog_fr.pdf Fran\u00e7ais] | [https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20080226230940/http://www.unaids.org/en/AboutUNAIDS/AboutTheWebsite/page_not_found.asp Espa\u00f1ol] | [https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20080226230940/http://www.unaids.org/en/AboutUNAIDS/AboutTheWebsite/page_not_found.asp \u0420\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439] | [http://data.unaids.org/pub/Biography/2007/0207peterpiotbiog_ar.pdf Arabic]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060918202802/http://www.unaids.org/en/AboutUNAIDS/Leadership/Speeches.asp Peter Piot - Latest Speeches]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060822061419/http://data.unaids.org/pub/ArticleExcerpt/2006/AIDS%20From%20Crisis%20Management%20to%20Sustained%20Strategic%20Response.pdf Peter Piot - Lancet Journal Article, August 6, 2006 (pdf, 83kb)]\n* [http://www.notimetolose-book.com/ No Time to Lose Official Website]\n* [http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b06zs3m2 BBC Radio 4 ''The Life Scientific'' programme about Peter Piot and his work on ebola and HIV AIDS, February 2016]\n*{{C-SPAN|Peter Piot}}\n\n{{Commission on HIV/AIDS and Governance in Africa}}\n{{Ebola}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Piot, Peter}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Barons of Belgium]]\n[[Category:Belgian microbiologists]]\n[[Category:HIV/AIDS researchers]]\n[[Category:HIV/AIDS activists]]\n[[Category:Honorary Knights Commander of the Order of St Michael and St George]]\n[[Category:Belgian officials of the United Nations]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Academy of Medicine]]\n[[Category:University of Antwerp alumni]]\n[[Category:Ghent University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Antwerp faculty]]\n[[Category:Academics of the London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine]]\n[[Category:Manson medal winners]]\n[[Category:People from Leuven]]\n[[Category:Grand Cordons of the Order of the Rising Sun]]\n[[Category:Ebola researchers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox scientist\n| honorific-prefix = Baron\n|name              = Peter Piot\n|image             = Baron_Peter_Piot.jpg\n|image_size        = 150px\n|caption           = Peter Piot\n|birth_date        = {{Birth date and age|1949|2|17|df=y}}\n|birth_place       = [[Leuven]], [[Belgium]]\n|death_date        = \n|death_place       = \n|residence         = \n|citizenship       = \n|nationality       = [[Belgium|Belgian]]\n|ethnicity         = \n|field             = \n|work_institutions = [[London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine]]<br>{{nowrap|[[Institute of Tropical Medicine Antwerp]]}}<br>[[Imperial College London]]\n|alma_mater        = [[Ghent University]]<br>[[University of Antwerp]]\n|doctoral_advisor  = \n|doctoral_students = \n|known_for         = \n|author_abbrev_bot = \n|author_abbrev_zoo = \n|influences        = \n|influenced        = \n|prizes            = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Calderone Award]] {{small|(2003)}}\n* [[Vlerick Award]] {{small|(2004)}}\n* Flanders-America Award {{small|(2008)}}\n* Prince Mahidol Award {{small|(2013)}}\n* Prix International de l\u2019INSERM {{small|(2015)}}\n* [[John Dirks Canada Gairdner Global Health Award]] {{small|(2015)}}\n* [[Manson Medal]] {{small|(2016)}}}}\n|website          = {{URL|http://www.lshtm.ac.uk/aboutus/people/piot.peter}}\n|footnotes         = \n}}\n'''Peter Karel, Baron Piot''', [[Order of St Michael and St George|KCMG]], [[Royal College of Physicians|FRCP]], [[Academy of Medical Sciences|FMedSci]] (born 17 February 1949) is a [[Belgium|Belgian]] microbiologist known for his research into [[Ebola]] and [[AIDS]]. After helping discover the Ebola virus in 1976 and leading efforts to contain the first-ever recorded Ebola epidemic that same year, Piot became a pioneering researcher into AIDS. He has held key positions in the [[United Nations]] and [[World Health Organization]] involving AIDS research and management. He has also served as a professor at several universities worldwide.<ref>{{cite book |last=Piot |first=P. |title=No Time to Lose: A Life in Pursuit of Deadly Viruses |location= |publisher=W. W. Norton |year=2012 |isbn= }}</ref> He is the author of 16 books and over 550 scientific articles.\n\n==Early life and education==\nPiot was born in [[Leuven]], [[Belgium]]. He studied medicine at [[Ghent University]], and earned an [[Doctor of Medicine|M.D.]] in 1974. He then began working at the [[Institute of Tropical Medicine Antwerp]] while pursuing a graduate degree in clinical [[microbiology]] from the [[University of Antwerp]]. He received a [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] in microbiology from the University of Antwerp in 1980.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lshtm.ac.uk/aboutus/people/piot.peter|title=Peter Piot|website=LSHTM|language=en|access-date=2017-07-27}}</ref>\n\nPiot is fluent in [[English language|English]], [[French language|French]], and [[Dutch language|Dutch]].<ref name=background/>\n\n==Career==\nIn 1976, while working at the Institute of Tropical Medicine, Piot was part of a team that discovered the [[Ebola]] virus in a sample of blood taken from a sick nun working in [[Zaire]].<ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(77)92002-5| title = Isolation of Marburg-Like Virus from a Case of H\u00e6morrhagic Fever in Zaire| journal = The Lancet| volume = 309| issue = 8011| pages = 573\u2013574| year = 1977| last1 = Pattyn | first1 = S.| last2 = Groen | first2 = G. V. | last3 = Jacob | first3 = W.| last4 = Piot | first4 = P.| last5 = Courteille | first5 = G. | pmid=65663}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1038/35073639| pmid = 11309626| title = The global impact of HIV/AIDS| journal = Nature| volume = 410| issue = 6831| pages = 968\u201373| year = 2001| last1 = Piot | first1 = P. | last2 = Bartos | first2 = M. | last3 = Ghys | first3 = P. D. | last4 = Walker | first4 = N. | last5 = Schwartl\u00e4nder | first5 = B. | bibcode = 2001Natur.410..968P}}</ref> Piot and his colleagues subsequently traveled to Zaire to help quell the outbreak. Piot's team made key discoveries into how the virus spread, and traveled from village to village, spreading information and putting the ill and those who had come into contact with them into quarantine. The epidemic was stopped in three months, after it had killed almost 300 people.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/magazine-28262541 The virus detective who discovered Ebola in 1976]</ref> The events were dramatised<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b04v5fjr |title= Ebola |publisher=[[BBC]]}}</ref> by [[Mike Walker (radio dramatist)|Mike Walker]] on [[BBC Radio 4]] in December 2014 in a production by [[David Morley (writer)|David Morley]]. Piot narrated the programme.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b04v5fjr|title=Ebola, Afternoon Drama - BBC Radio 4|website=BBC|access-date=2017-07-27}}</ref>\n\nPiot has received the majority of the credit for discovering Ebola, since in 1976, he was the one to receive blood samples while working in a lab at the Institute for Tropical Medicine in Antwerp, Belgium.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.lshtm.ac.uk/aboutus/people/piot.peter |title = Peter Piot}}</ref> The samples were originally sent by Dr. [[Jean-Jacques Muyembe-Tamfum]], a Congolese doctor who obtained the blood samples from those sickened with a mysterious disease in then-Zaire, later discovered to be Ebola. In 2012, Piot published a memoir entitled ''No Time to Lose'' which chronicles his professional work, including the discovery of the Ebolavirus; he mentions Muyembe in passing rather than as a co-discoverer. Piot stated in 2019 that \"my book was not an attempt to write the history of Ebola, but more my personal experience\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2019/11/04/774863495/this-congolese-doctor-discovered-ebola-but-never-got-credit-for-it-until-now |title=This Congolese Doctor Discovered Ebola But Never Got Credit For It \u2014 Until Now |author=Eyder Peralta |publisher=NPR |date=November 4, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nIn the 1980s, Piot participated in a series of collaborative projects in Burundi, C\u00f4te d'Ivoire, Kenya, Tanzania, and Zaire. Project SIDA in Kinshasa, Zaire was the first international project on [[AIDS]] in Africa and is widely acknowledged as having provided the foundations of science's understanding of [[HIV]] infection in Africa. He was a professor of [[microbiology]], and of [[public health]] at the [[Prince Leopold Institute of Tropical Medicine]], in [[Antwerp]], and at the [[University of Nairobi]], [[Vrije Universiteit Brussel]], the [[University of Lausanne|Lausanne]], and a visiting professor at the [[London School of Economics]]. He was also a Senior Fellow at the [[University of Washington]] in Seattle, a Scholar in Residence at the [[Ford Foundation]], and a Senior Fellow at the [[Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation]].<ref name=background/>\n\nFrom 1991 to 1994, Piot was president of the [[International AIDS Society]]. In 1992, he became Assistant Director of the [[World Health Organization]]'s ''Global Programme on HIV/AIDS''. On 12 December 1994, he was appointed Executive Director of the ''[[Joint United Nations Programme on HIV/AIDS]]'' (UNAIDS) and Assistant-Secretary-General of the United Nations.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(08)60820-X| title = Peter Piot| journal = The Lancet| volume = 371| issue = 9628| pages = 1907| year = 2008| last1 = Shetty | first1 = P.| pmid=18539213}}</ref> \n\nFrom 2009 to 2010, Piot served as director of the Institute for Global Health at [[Imperial College London]].<ref name=background>[http://www.lshtm.ac.uk/aboutus/people/piot.peter Professor Peter Piot]</ref> \n\n===London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine===\nIn September 2010,{{citation needed|date=May 2017}} Piot became the director of the [[London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.lshtm.ac.uk/aboutus/introducing/welcome-director |title=Welcome from the Director |publisher=[[London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine]] |accessdate=6 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to his work at LSHTM, Piot is a member of the [[Institute of Medicine]] of the [[United States National Academy of Sciences|National Academy of Sciences of the United States]] and the Royal Academy of Medicine of Belgium, a Fellow of the [[Royal College of Physicians of London]], UK and a Fellow of the [[Academy of Medical Sciences]]. In 2011, [[Amy Gutmann]] appointed him to serve on the International Research Panel at the [[Presidential Commission for the Study of Bioethical Issues]]. \n\nIn 2014, in the face of an unprecedented [[2014 West Africa Ebola outbreak|Ebola epidemic in western Africa]], Piot and other scientists called for the emergency release of the experimental [[ZMapp]] vaccine for use on humans before it had undergone clinical testing on humans.<ref>{{cite web|date=6 August 2014 |url=http://www.latimes.com/world/africa/la-fg-three-ebola-experts-release-drugs-20140806-story.html|title=Three leading Ebola experts call for release of experimental drug|work=Los Angeles Times}}</ref> That year, he was appointed by Director General [[Margaret Chan]] to the [[World Health Organization]]'s Advisory Group on the Ebola Virus Disease Response, co-chaired by [[Sam Zaramba]] and [[David L. Heymann]].<ref>[https://www.who.int/csr/disease/ebola/advisory-groups/members/en/ Members of the WHO Advisory Group on the Ebola Virus Disease Response] [[World Health Organization]].</ref> He also chaired an independent panel convened by Harvard Global Health Institute and the London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine into the national and international response to the epidemic, which sharply criticised the response of the WHO and put forward ten recommendations for the body's reorganisation.<ref>{{citation|url= |title=Will Ebola change the game? Ten essential reforms before the next pandemic. The report of the Harvard-LSHTM Independent Panel on the Global Response to Ebola |author=Moon S |journal=Lancet |volume=386 |issue=10009 |pages=2204\u20132221 |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(15)00946-0|display-authors=etal |pmid=26615326|year=2015 }}</ref> In February 2020, he criticised the delay in declaring the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2019\u201320 novel coronavirus outbreak]] focused on [[Hubei]], China, a [[Public Health Emergency of International Concern]], and advocated a five-point scale for outbreaks, rather the current binary (emergency/no emergency) system.<ref>{{cite podcast |url=https://anchor.fm/lshtm/episodes/S1E5-Coronavirus---will-it-become-a-pandemic-eamji1 |title=Coronavirus - will it become a pandemic? (''LSHTM Viral'' S1E5) |time=06:34\u201307:56 |host=Peter Piot, James Barr |publisher=[[London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine]] |date=February 7, 2020 |accessdate=February 9, 2010  }}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, Piot was appointed to the [[European Commission]]\u2019s advisory panel on [[COVID-19]], co-chaired by [[Ursula von der Leyen]] and [[Stella Kyriakides]].<ref>[https://ec.europa.eu/commission/presscorner/detail/en/ip_20_481 COVID-19: Commission launches European team of scientific experts to strengthen EU coordination and medical response] [[European Commission]], press release of March 17, 2020.</ref>\n\n==Other activities==\n===Non-profit organizations===\n* [[Coalition for Epidemic Preparedness Innovations]] (CEPI), Member of the Board (since 2018)<ref>[https://cepi.net/about/whoweare/ Board] [[Coalition for Epidemic Preparedness Innovations]] (CEPI).</ref><ref>[https://cepi.net/news_cepi/cepi-announces-new-permanent-board/ CEPI announces new permanent board] [[Coalition for Epidemic Preparedness Innovations]] (CEPI), press release of January 24, 2018.</ref>\n* Africa Health Research Institute (AHRI), Chair of the Board of Directors (since 2017)<ref>[https://www.ahri.org/structure-governance/ Governance] Africa Health Research Institute (AHRI).</ref>[https://www.ahri.org/olive-shisana-peter-piot-appointed-africa-health-research-institute-board/ Olive Shisana and Peter Piot appointed to Africa Health Research Institute Board] Africa Health Research Institute (AHRI), press release of January 31, 2017.</ref>\n* UK Collaborative on Development Research (UKCDR), Chair of the Strategic Coherence of ODA-funded Research (since 2017)<ref>[https://www.ukcdr.org.uk/about-us/our-governance/ Strategic Coherence of ODA-funded Research] UK Collaborative on Development Research (UKCDR).</ref><ref>[https://www.ukcdr.org.uk/news-article/announcing-the-chair-of-the-new-hmg-scor-board/ Announcing the Chair of the new HMG SCOR Board] UK Collaborative on Development Research (UKCDR), press release of September 26, 2017.</ref>\n* Africa Research Excellence Fund (AREF), Member of the Advisory Panel (since 2015)<ref>[http://www.africaresearchexcellencefund.org.uk/about-us/our-governance/our-advisory-panel/ Advisory Panel] Africa Research Excellence Fund (AREF).</ref>\n* [[Novartis Foundation]], Member of the Board of Trustees (since 2015)<ref>[https://www.novartisfoundation.org/about-us/board-trustees Board of Trustees] [[Novartis Foundation]].</ref><ref>[https://www.novartis.com/news/media-releases/novartis-foundation-confirms-new-members-its-board-trustees-including-new-chairman-dr-joerg-reinhardt Novartis Foundation confirms new members of its Board of trustees, including new Chairman Dr. Joerg Reinhardt] [[Novartis Foundation]], press release of July 27, 2015.</ref>\n* [[Antwerp Management School]], Member of the International Advisory Board<ref>[https://www.antwerpmanagementschool.be/en/about/international-advisory-board International Advisory Board] [[Antwerp Management School]].</ref> \n* Centre Virchow-Villerm\u00e9, Member of the International Advisory Board<ref>[https://virchowvillerme.eu/international-advisory-board-2/ International Advisory Board] Centre Virchow-Villerm\u00e9.</ref>\n* [[Global Health Innovative Technology Fund (GHIT)|Global Health Innovative Technology Fund]] (GHIT), Member of the Board of Directors<ref>[https://www.ghitfund.org/leadership/boardofdirectors Board of Directors] Global Health Innovative Technology Fund (GHIT Fund).</ref>\n* [[University of Washington]], External Member of the Advisory Board at the Department of Global Health<ref>[https://globalhealth.washington.edu/peter-piot Peter Piot] [[University of Washington]].</ref>\n* [[World Health Summit]], Member of the Council<ref>[https://www.worldhealthsummit.org/about-whs/leadership.html Council] [[World Health Summit]].</ref>\n===Editorial boards===\n* ''[[The Lancet]]'', Member of the International Advisory Board<ref>[https://www.thelancet.com/lancet/international-advisory-board International Advisory Board] ''[[The Lancet]]''.</ref>\n* ''[[The Lancet|The Lancet Public Health]]'', Member of the Editorial Advisory Board (since 2016)<ref>[https://www.thelancet.com/lanpub/editorial-advisory-board Editorial Advisory Board] ''[[The Lancet]]''.</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\n===Awards===\n* Calderone Prize in Public Health (2003)<ref name=\"Calderone\">{{cite web | title=Past Recipients | website=Columbia University Mailman School of Public Health | date=8 September 2018 | url=https://www.mailman.columbia.edu/public-health-now/events/distinguished-lectures/calderone-prize/past-recipients | access-date=17 October 2018}}</ref> \n* [[Vlerick Award]] (2004)\n* America-Flanders Award (2008)<ref name=\"Flanders\">{{cite web | trans-title=Flanders-America Awards for Peter Piot and Bruyneel/Armstrong duo| title=Flanders-America Awards voor Peter Piot en duo Bruyneel/Armstrong | website=Het Nieuwsblad Mobile | date=25 February 2009 | url=https://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/dmf26022009_007 | language=nl | access-date=17 October 2018}}</ref> \n* [[Hideyo Noguchi Africa Prize]] (2013),<ref name=\"Noguchi\">{{cite news | last=Osaki | first=Tomohiro | title=Belgian, Ugandan win Noguchi prize | newspaper=The Japan Times Online | date=2 June 2013 | url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2013/06/02/national/politics-diplomacy/belgian-ugandan-win-noguchi-prize/ | access-date=17 October 2018}}</ref> \n* Prince Mahidol Award (2013)<ref name=\"Mahidol\">{{cite journal | last=Holmes | first=David | title=2013 Prince Mahidol Award winners announced | journal=The Lancet | volume=382 | issue=9908 | year=2013 | issn=0140-6736 | doi=10.1016/s0140-6736(13)62349-1 | pmid=24325009 | page=1869}}</ref> \n* Prix International de l\u2019INSERM (2015)<ref name=\"INSERM\">{{cite web | author= histoire | title=Peter Piot, Prix International 2015 / Histoire de l'Inserm | website=Histoire de l'Inserm | url=https://histoire.inserm.fr/de-l-inh-a-l-inserm/les-prix-inserm/prix-2015/peter-piot-prix-international-2015 | language=fr | access-date=17 October 2018}}</ref> \n* [[Canada Gairdner Global Health Award]] (2015)<ref name=\"Dirks\">{{cite journal | last=Maurice | first=John | title=Peter Piot wins 2015 Canada Gairdner Global Health Award | journal=The Lancet | volume=385 | issue=9974 | year=2015 | issn=0140-6736 | doi=10.1016/s0140-6736(15)60610-9 | pmid=25819690 | page=1170}}</ref> \n* [[Manson Medal]] (2016)<ref name=\"Manson\">{{cite web | title=Previous medal winners | website=Royal Society of Tropical Medicine and Hygiene | date=6 August 2014 | url=https://rstmh.org/awards/previous-medal-winners | access-date=17 October 2018}}</ref> \n\n===Honours===\n* [[Image:UK Order St-Michael St-George ribbon.svg|Ruban|45px]] Honorary Knight Commander of the [[Order of St Michael and St George]] (2016) \n*[[File:JPN Kyokujitsu-sho 1Class BAR.svg|45px|ribbon bar]] Grand Cordon of the [[Order of the Rising Sun]] (2018)\n\nPiot was appointed an Officer of the Order of the Leopard of Zaire in 1976 for his work during the Ebola outbreak, and was also appointed an Officer of the Order of the Lion of Senegal. He was ennobled as a Baron by King [[Albert II of Belgium]], in 1995. In 2016, he was made an honorary Knight Commander of the [[Order of St Michael and St George]] in the United Kingdom.<ref>[https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/581724/2016_Honorary_awards_V4.pdf Honorary awards]</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* Peter Piot - Biography (UNAIDS.org): [http://data.unaids.org/pub/Biography/2007/0207peterpiotbiog_en.pdf English] | [http://data.unaids.org/pub/Biography/2007/0207peterpiotbiog_fr.pdf Fran\u00e7ais] | [https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20080226230940/http://www.unaids.org/en/AboutUNAIDS/AboutTheWebsite/page_not_found.asp Espa\u00f1ol] | [https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20080226230940/http://www.unaids.org/en/AboutUNAIDS/AboutTheWebsite/page_not_found.asp \u0420\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439] | [http://data.unaids.org/pub/Biography/2007/0207peterpiotbiog_ar.pdf Arabic]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060918202802/http://www.unaids.org/en/AboutUNAIDS/Leadership/Speeches.asp Peter Piot - Latest Speeches]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060822061419/http://data.unaids.org/pub/ArticleExcerpt/2006/AIDS%20From%20Crisis%20Management%20to%20Sustained%20Strategic%20Response.pdf Peter Piot - Lancet Journal Article, August 6, 2006 (pdf, 83kb)]\n* [http://www.notimetolose-book.com/ No Time to Lose Official Website]\n* [http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b06zs3m2 BBC Radio 4 ''The Life Scientific'' programme about Peter Piot and his work on ebola and HIV AIDS, February 2016]\n*{{C-SPAN|Peter Piot}}\n\n{{Commission on HIV/AIDS and Governance in Africa}}\n{{Ebola}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Piot, Peter}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Barons of Belgium]]\n[[Category:Belgian microbiologists]]\n[[Category:HIV/AIDS researchers]]\n[[Category:HIV/AIDS activists]]\n[[Category:Honorary Knights Commander of the Order of St Michael and St George]]\n[[Category:Belgian officials of the United Nations]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Academy of Medicine]]\n[[Category:University of Antwerp alumni]]\n[[Category:Ghent University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Antwerp faculty]]\n[[Category:Academics of the London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine]]\n[[Category:Manson medal winners]]\n[[Category:People from Leuven]]\n[[Category:Grand Cordons of the Order of the Rising Sun]]\n[[Category:Ebola researchers]]\n", "name_user": "MSPH Wiki", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peter_Piot"}
{"title_page": "Ian Cardozo", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix = [[Major general#India|Major General]]\n| name          = Ian Cardozo\n| honorific_suffix = [[Ati Vishisht Seva Medal|AVSM]] [[Sena Medal|SM]]\n| image         = Ian Cardozo.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| native_name   = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name    = \n| other_name    = \n| nickname      = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1937|8|7}}<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web|last1=Singh|first1=Aarti|title=10 Indian Soldiers Whose Courageous And Patriotic Stories Need To Be Retold|url=http://www.polkacafe.com/patriotic-stories-of-indian-soldiers-3069.html|website=Polkacafe.com|date=12 Aug 2016}}</ref>\n| birth_place   = [[Bombay]], [[Bombay Presidency]], [[British Raj|British India]]\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} death date first, then birth date -->\n| death_place   = \n| placeofburial_label = \n| placeofburial = \n| placeofburial_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n| allegiance    = [[India]]\n| branch        = [[Indian Army]]\n| serviceyears  = 1954\u20131993\n| serviceyears_label = \n| rank          = [[Major General]]\n| rank_label    = \n| servicenumber = IC-10407<ref>{{cite news |title=Part I-Section 4: Ministry of Defence (Army Branch) |page=1814  |date=22 November 1986 |website= |publisher=The Gazette of India}}</ref>\n| unit          = 1/[[5 Gorkha Rifles]] & 4/[[5 Gorkha Rifles]]\n| commands      = \n| battles_label = \n| battles       = {{Unbulleted list|\n[[Indo-Pakistani War of 1971]]|\n{{*}}[[Battle of Sylhet]]\n}}\n| awards        = [[Ati Vishisht Seva Medal]]<br>[[Sena Medal]]<ref name=\"adapt\">{{cite news|last1=PISHAROTY|first1=SANGEETA BAROOAH|title=Unknown soldier... to you I bow|url=http://www.thehindu.com/thehindu/mp/2003/02/13/stories/2003021300110300.htm|work=[[The Hindu]]|date=13 Feb 2003}}</ref>\n| memorials     = \n| spouse        = Priscilla Cardozo\n| relations     = \n| children      = 3\n| laterwork     = {{plainlist|\n* Former Chairman \u2013 [[Rehabilitation Council of India]]\n* [[Trustee]] \u2013 [[National Centre for Promotion of Employment for Disabled People]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Trustees \u2013 NCPEDP|url=http://www.ncpedp.org/Trustees|publisher=[[NCPEDP]]|accessdate=17 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n}}\n| signature     = \n| signature_size = \n| signature_alt = \n| website       = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| module        = \n}}\n\n[[Major General]] '''Ian Cardozo''' [[Ati Vishisht Seva Medal|AVSM]] [[Sena Medal|SM]] is a former [[Indian Army]] officer. He was the first war-disabled officer of the Indian Army to command a [[battalion]] and a [[brigade]].<ref name=\"interview\">{{cite news|last1=Claude|first1=Arpi|title=1971, A War Hero Remembers|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/slide-show/slide-show-1-a-war-hero-remembers/20111207.htm|work=[[Rediff.com]]|date=8 Dec 2011}}</ref> He is an [[Amputation|amputee]] due to a war injury.<ref name=\"bio\" />\n\n==Early life==\nIan Cardozo was born to Vincent Cardozo and Diana (n\u00e9e de Souza) Cardozo in 1937 in [[Bombay]], [[Bombay Presidency]], [[British Raj|British India]]. He studied at [[St. Xavier's College, Mumbai]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Param Vir: Our Heroes in Battle|last1=Cardozo|first1=Ian|date=2003|publisher=Roli Books|isbn=9351940292|pages=228}}</ref> \n\n==Military career==\nCardozo graduated from the [[National Defence Academy (India)|National Defence Academy]] and then attended the [[Indian Military Academy]], from where he joined the [[5 Gorkha Rifles]] ('''Frontier Force''') and he was commissioned & later commanded the 1st Battalion of the 5th Regiment of Gorkha RIfles aka \"1/5GR(FF) or  1/[[5 Gorkha Rifles]].\nHe also has also served with 4/ [[5 Gorkha Rifles]] and has fought 2 wars alongside them-[[Indo-Pakistani War of 1965]] and the [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1971]].<ref name=\"adapt\" />. He is the first NDA cadet to receive both Gold and Silver medals. <ref name=\"sdfbook\" /> \n\n===Indo-Pakistani War of 1971===\nAt the outbreak of the [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1971]], Cardozo was attending a course at the [[Defence Services Staff College]], [[Wellington Cantonment|Wellington]]. His battalion, 4/5 Gorkha Rifles, was already deployed in the eastern theatre of operations. The battalion's second-in-command was martyred in action and Cardozo was ordered to replace him. He arrived at his battalion in time to accompany them on the Indian Army's first heliborne operation during the [[battle of Sylhet]].<ref name=\"selfampute\" />. He was popularly named ''Cartoos [[sahib]]'' by his Gorkha regiment as they found it difficult to pronounce his first name.<ref name=\"sdfbook\">{{cite book |last1=Bisht Rawat |first1=Rachna |title=Shoot, Dive, Fly : Stories of Grit and Adventure from The Indian Army |date=15 Oct 2017 |publisher=Penguin Random House India Private Limited |isbn=9386651696 |pages=208}}</ref> Cartoos means a cartridge in [[Hindi]].\n\nAfter the fall of [[Dhaka]], Cardozo stepped on a [[land mine]] and his leg was critically injured. Due to non-availability of [[morphine]] or [[pethidine]], and absence of medics, his leg could not be amputated surgically. He subsequently used his [[khukri]] to amputate his own leg. Afterwards, his unit captured a [[Pakistan Army]] surgeon, Maj. Mohammad Basheer, who operated on Cardozo.<ref name=\"selfampute\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/slide-show/slide-show-1-ian-cardozo-i-cut-my-leg-off-and-ordered-go-and-bury-it/20111208.htm|title='I cut my leg off and ordered: 'Go and bury it'|last1=Arpi|first1=Claude|date=8 Dec 2011|publisher=[[Rediff.com]]}}</ref>\n\n===Later career===\nAfter his amputation, Cardozo had a wooden leg. Despite this, he maintained his physical fitness levels and beat a number of able-bodied officers in battle physical fitness tests. He then put his case to the [[Chief of Army Staff (India)|Chief of Army Staff]] at the time, Gen. [[Tapishwar Narain Raina]], who then asked Cardozo to accompany him to [[Ladakh]]. After observing that Cardozo could still walk in the mountains through snow and ice, Gen. Raina allowed him to command a battalion. A similar situation occurred when he was to take command of a brigade.<ref name=\"selfampute\" /> He was promoted to brigadier on 1 March 1984.<ref>{{cite news |title=Part I-Section 4: Ministry of Defence (Army Branch) |page=338  |date=7 March 1987 |website= |publisher=The Gazette of India}}</ref>\n\n=== Military Awards and Decorations ===\n\n<center>\n{|\n|-\n|\n|[[File:Ati Vishisht Seva Medal ribbon.svg|105px]]\n|[[File:Sena Medal ribbon.svg|105px]]\n|\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[File:Wound Medal-India.svg|105px]] [[File:India General Service Medal 1947.svg|105px]] [[File:IND Samar Seva Star Ribbon.svg|105px]]\n|-\n|[[File:IND Poorvi Star Ribbon.svg|105px]]\n|[[File:IND Raksha Medal Ribbon.svg|105px]]\n|[[File:IND Sangram Medal Ribbon.svg|105px]]\n|[[File:IND Sainya Seva Medal Ribbon.svg|105px]]\n|-\n|[[File:IND 25th Anniversary Independence medal.svg|105px]]\n|[[File:IND 30 Years Long Service Ribbon.svg|105px]]\n|[[File:IND 20YearsServiceMedalRibbon.svg|105px]]\n|[[File:IND 9YearsServiceMedalRibbon.svg|105px]]\n|-\n|}\n</center>\n\n<center>\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" |[[Ati Vishisht Seva Medal]]\n|colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" |[[Sena Medal]]\n|-\n|colspan=\"1\" align=\"center\" |[[Wound Medal (India)|Wound Medal]]\n|colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" |[[General Service Medal 1947|General Service Medal]]\n|colspan=\"1\" align=\"center\" |[[Indian military decorations#Service and campaign medals|Samar Seva Medal]]\n|-\n|<center>[[Poorvi Star]]</center>\n|<center>[[Indian military decorations#Service and campaign medals|Raksha Medal]]</center>\n|<center>[[Sangram Medal]]</center>\n|<center>[[Indian military decorations#Service and campaign medals|Sainya Seva Medal]]</center>\n|-\n|<center>[[Indian military decorations#Service and campaign medals|25th Anniversary of Independence Medal]]</center>\n|<center>[[Indian military decorations#Service and campaign medals|30 Years Long Service Medal]]</center>\n|<center>[[Indian military decorations#Service and campaign medals|20 Years Long Service Medal]]</center>\n|<center>[[Indian military decorations#Service and campaign medals|9 Years Long Service Medal]]</center>\n|-\n|}\n</center>\n\n== Personal life ==\nCardozo is married to Priscilla and has three sons.<ref name=\"interview\" /> He currently resides in [[New Delhi]].<ref name=\"adapt\" />\n\nHe served as the Chairman of Rehabilitation Council of India from 2005 to 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rehabcouncil.nic.in/forms/Sublink1.aspx?lid=823|title=RCI \u2013 Annual Reports|publisher=[[Rehabilitation Council of India]]|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> He is also a marathon runner, and regularly takes part in the Mumbai marathon on his prosthetic limbs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/lifestyle/viral-and-trending/220118/running-for-causes.html|title=Running for causes|last1=Das|first1=Sucharita|date=22 Jan 2018|work=[[Deccan Chronicle]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.asianage.com/life/more-features/220118/mumbai-runs-with-all-its-heart.html|title=Mumbai runs, with all its heart|last1=Salvi|first1=Pooja|date=22 Jan 2018|work=[[The Asian Age]]}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\nHe authored several books on military history of India:-\n\n* Bhartiya Sena Ka Gauravshali Itihas {{ISBN|8173155372}}\n* India in World War I: An Illustrated Story {{ISBN|9789384898502}}\n* Lieutenant General Bilimoria: His Life & Times<ref>{{cite news|last1=Filmer|first1=Antonia|title=\u2018In the Army, work and play are synonymous\u2019|url=http://www.sundayguardianlive.com/opinion/5863-army-work-and-play-are-synonymous|work=[[The Sunday Guardian]]|date=30 Jul 2016}}</ref>\n* Param Vir: Our Heroes in Battle {{ISBN|9351940292}}\n* Paramvir Chakra : Manojpandey {{ISBN|8174369007}}\n* Somnath Sharma: Hero of the Battle of Badgam in 1947 who Helped Prevent the Fall of Srinagar {{ISBN|8174369236}}\n* Shaitan Singh: Incredible Heroism Displayed by a Small Group Against Hordes of Chinese in the Battle of Rezang La in 1962 {{ISBN|8174369155}}\n* The Bravest of the Brave: The Extraordinary Story of Indian VCs of World War I {{ISBN|9789386141767}}\n* The Indian Army: A Brief History {{ISBN|8190209701}}\n* The Sinking of INS Khukri: Survivor's Stories {{ISBN|9351940993}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[F. N. Billimoria]]\n*[[Yogendra Singh Yadav]]\n*[[Zorawar Chand Bakhshi]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://claudearpi.blogspot.com/2011/12/forty-years-after-general-cardozos.html Forty Years After: General Cardozo's incredible story]\n\n{{Ati Vishisht Seva Medal recipients}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cardozo, Ian}}\n[[Category:Indian generals]]\n[[Category:Indian amputees]]\n[[Category:Indian military personnel of the Indo-Pakistani War of 1971]]\n[[Category:Indian disability rights activists]]\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:Indian military historians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Ati Vishisht Seva Medal]]\n[[Category:Indian Military Academy alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix = [[Major general#India|Major General]]\n| name          = Ian Cardozo\n| honorific_suffix = [[Ati Vishisht Seva Medal|AVSM]] [[Sena Medal|SM]]\n| image         = Ian Cardozo.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| native_name   = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name    = \n| other_name    = \n| nickname      = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1937|8|7}}<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web|last1=Singh|first1=Aarti|title=10 Indian Soldiers Whose Courageous And Patriotic Stories Need To Be Retold|url=http://www.polkacafe.com/patriotic-stories-of-indian-soldiers-3069.html|website=Polkacafe.com|date=12 Aug 2016}}</ref>\n| birth_place   = [[Bombay]], [[Bombay Presidency]], [[British Raj|British India]]\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} death date first, then birth date -->\n| death_place   = \n| placeofburial_label = \n| placeofburial = \n| placeofburial_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n| allegiance    = [[India]]\n| branch        = [[Indian Army]]\n| serviceyears  = 1954\u20131993\n| serviceyears_label = \n| rank          = [[Major General]]\n| rank_label    = \n| servicenumber = IC-10407<ref>{{cite news |title=Part I-Section 4: Ministry of Defence (Army Branch) |page=1814  |date=22 November 1986 |website= |publisher=The Gazette of India}}</ref>\n| unit          = 1/[[5 Gorkha Rifles]] & 4/[[5 Gorkha Rifles]]\n| commands      = \n| battles_label = \n| battles       = {{Unbulleted list|\n[[Indo-Pakistani War of 1971]]|\n{{*}}[[Battle of Sylhet]]\n}}\n| awards        = [[Ati Vishisht Seva Medal]]<br>[[Sena Medal]]<ref name=\"adapt\">{{cite news|last1=PISHAROTY|first1=SANGEETA BAROOAH|title=Unknown soldier... to you I bow|url=http://www.thehindu.com/thehindu/mp/2003/02/13/stories/2003021300110300.htm|work=[[The Hindu]]|date=13 Feb 2003}}</ref>\n| memorials     = \n| spouse        = Priscilla Cardozo\n| relations     = \n| children      = 3\n| laterwork     = {{plainlist|\n* Former Chairman \u2013 [[Rehabilitation Council of India]]\n* [[Trustee]] \u2013 [[National Centre for Promotion of Employment for Disabled People]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Trustees \u2013 NCPEDP|url=http://www.ncpedp.org/Trustees|publisher=[[NCPEDP]]|accessdate=17 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n}}\n| signature     = \n| signature_size = \n| signature_alt = \n| website       = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| module        = \n}}\n\n[[Major General]] '''Ian Cardozo''' [[Ati Vishisht Seva Medal|AVSM]] [[Sena Medal|SM]] is a former [[Indian Army]] officer. He was the first war-disabled officer of the Indian Army to command a [[battalion]] and a [[brigade]].<ref name=\"interview\">{{cite news|last1=Claude|first1=Arpi|title=1971, A War Hero Remembers|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/slide-show/slide-show-1-a-war-hero-remembers/20111207.htm|work=[[Rediff.com]]|date=8 Dec 2011}}</ref> He is an [[Amputation|amputee]] due to a war injury.<ref name=\"bio\" />\n\n==Early life==\nIan Cardozo was born to Vincent Cardozo and Diana (nee de Souza) Cardozo in 1937 in [[Bombay]], [[Bombay Presidency]], [[British Raj|British India]]. He studied at [[St. Xavier's College, Mumbai]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Param Vir: Our Heroes in Battle|last1=Cardozo|first1=Ian|date=2003|publisher=Roli Books|isbn=9351940292|pages=228}}</ref> \n\n==Military career==\nCardozo graduated from the [[National Defence Academy (India)|National Defence Academy]] and then attended the [[Indian Military Academy]], from where he joined the [[5 Gorkha Rifles]] ('''Frontier Force''') and he was commissioned & later commanded the 1st Battalion of the 5th Regiment of Gorkha RIfles aka \"1/5GR(FF) or  1/[[5 Gorkha Rifles]].\nHe also has also served with 4/ [[5 Gorkha Rifles]] and has fought 2 wars alongside them-[[Indo-Pakistani War of 1965]] and the [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1971]].<ref name=\"adapt\" />. He is the first NDA cadet to receive both Gold and Silver medals. <ref name=\"sdfbook\" /> \n\n===Indo-Pakistani War of 1971===\nAt the outbreak of the [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1971]], Cardozo was attending a course at the [[Defence Services Staff College]], [[Wellington Cantonment|Wellington]]. His battalion, 4/5 Gorkha Rifles, was already deployed in the eastern theatre of operations. The battalion's second-in-command was martyred in action and Cardozo was ordered to replace him. He arrived at his battalion in time to accompany them on the Indian Army's first heliborne operation during the [[battle of Sylhet]].<ref name=\"selfampute\" />. He was popularly named ''Cartoos [[sahib]]'' by his Gorkha regiment as they found it difficult to pronounce his first name.<ref name=\"sdfbook\">{{cite book |last1=Bisht Rawat |first1=Rachna |title=Shoot, Dive, Fly : Stories of Grit and Adventure from The Indian Army |date=15 Oct 2017 |publisher=Penguin Random House India Private Limited |isbn=9386651696 |pages=208}}</ref> Cartoos means a cartridge in [[Hindi]].\n\nAfter the fall of [[Dhaka]], Cardozo stepped on a [[land mine]] and his leg was critically injured. Due to non-availability of [[morphine]] or [[pethidine]], and absence of medics, his leg could not be amputated surgically. He subsequently used his [[khukri]] to amputate his own leg. Afterwards, his unit captured a [[Pakistan Army]] surgeon, Maj. Mohammad Basheer, who operated on Cardozo.<ref name=\"selfampute\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/slide-show/slide-show-1-ian-cardozo-i-cut-my-leg-off-and-ordered-go-and-bury-it/20111208.htm|title='I cut my leg off and ordered: 'Go and bury it'|last1=Arpi|first1=Claude|date=8 Dec 2011|publisher=[[Rediff.com]]}}</ref>\n\n===Later career===\nAfter his amputation, Cardozo had a wooden leg. Despite this, he maintained his physical fitness levels and beat a number of able-bodied officers in battle physical fitness tests. He then put his case to the [[Chief of Army Staff (India)|Chief of Army Staff]] at the time, Gen. [[Tapishwar Narain Raina]], who then asked Cardozo to accompany him to [[Ladakh]]. After observing that Cardozo could still walk in the mountains through snow and ice, Gen. Raina allowed him to command a battalion. A similar situation occurred when he was to take command of a brigade.<ref name=\"selfampute\" /> He was promoted to brigadier on 1 March 1984.<ref>{{cite news |title=Part I-Section 4: Ministry of Defence (Army Branch) |page=338  |date=7 March 1987 |website= |publisher=The Gazette of India}}</ref>\n\n=== Military Awards and Decorations ===\n\n<center>\n{|\n|-\n|\n|[[File:Ati Vishisht Seva Medal ribbon.svg|105px]]\n|[[File:Sena Medal ribbon.svg|105px]]\n|\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\" align=\"center\" |[[File:Wound Medal-India.svg|105px]] [[File:India General Service Medal 1947.svg|105px]] [[File:IND Samar Seva Star Ribbon.svg|105px]]\n|-\n|[[File:IND Poorvi Star Ribbon.svg|105px]]\n|[[File:IND Raksha Medal Ribbon.svg|105px]]\n|[[File:IND Sangram Medal Ribbon.svg|105px]]\n|[[File:IND Sainya Seva Medal Ribbon.svg|105px]]\n|-\n|[[File:IND 25th Anniversary Independence medal.svg|105px]]\n|[[File:IND 30 Years Long Service Ribbon.svg|105px]]\n|[[File:IND 20YearsServiceMedalRibbon.svg|105px]]\n|[[File:IND 9YearsServiceMedalRibbon.svg|105px]]\n|-\n|}\n</center>\n\n<center>\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" |[[Ati Vishisht Seva Medal]]\n|colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" |[[Sena Medal]]\n|-\n|colspan=\"1\" align=\"center\" |[[Wound Medal (India)|Wound Medal]]\n|colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" |[[General Service Medal 1947|General Service Medal]]\n|colspan=\"1\" align=\"center\" |[[Indian military decorations#Service and campaign medals|Samar Seva Medal]]\n|-\n|<center>[[Poorvi Star]]</center>\n|<center>[[Indian military decorations#Service and campaign medals|Raksha Medal]]</center>\n|<center>[[Sangram Medal]]</center>\n|<center>[[Indian military decorations#Service and campaign medals|Sainya Seva Medal]]</center>\n|-\n|<center>[[Indian military decorations#Service and campaign medals|25th Anniversary of Independence Medal]]</center>\n|<center>[[Indian military decorations#Service and campaign medals|30 Years Long Service Medal]]</center>\n|<center>[[Indian military decorations#Service and campaign medals|20 Years Long Service Medal]]</center>\n|<center>[[Indian military decorations#Service and campaign medals|9 Years Long Service Medal]]</center>\n|-\n|}\n</center>\n\n== Personal life ==\nCardozo is married to Priscilla and has three sons.<ref name=\"interview\" /> He currently resides in [[New Delhi]].<ref name=\"adapt\" />\n\nHe served as the Chairman of Rehabilitation Council of India from 2005 to 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rehabcouncil.nic.in/forms/Sublink1.aspx?lid=823|title=RCI \u2013 Annual Reports|publisher=[[Rehabilitation Council of India]]|accessdate=16 May 2017}}</ref> He is also a marathon runner, and regularly takes part in the Mumbai marathon on his prosthetic limbs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/lifestyle/viral-and-trending/220118/running-for-causes.html|title=Running for causes|last1=Das|first1=Sucharita|date=22 Jan 2018|work=[[Deccan Chronicle]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.asianage.com/life/more-features/220118/mumbai-runs-with-all-its-heart.html|title=Mumbai runs, with all its heart|last1=Salvi|first1=Pooja|date=22 Jan 2018|work=[[The Asian Age]]}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\nHe authored several books on military history of India:-\n\n* Bhartiya Sena Ka Gauravshali Itihas {{ISBN|8173155372}}\n* India in World War I: An Illustrated Story {{ISBN|9789384898502}}\n* Lieutenant General Bilimoria: His Life & Times<ref>{{cite news|last1=Filmer|first1=Antonia|title=\u2018In the Army, work and play are synonymous\u2019|url=http://www.sundayguardianlive.com/opinion/5863-army-work-and-play-are-synonymous|work=[[The Sunday Guardian]]|date=30 Jul 2016}}</ref>\n* Param Vir: Our Heroes in Battle {{ISBN|9351940292}}\n* Paramvir Chakra : Manojpandey {{ISBN|8174369007}}\n* Somnath Sharma: Hero of the Battle of Badgam in 1947 who Helped Prevent the Fall of Srinagar {{ISBN|8174369236}}\n* Shaitan Singh: Incredible Heroism Displayed by a Small Group Against Hordes of Chinese in the Battle of Rezang La in 1962 {{ISBN|8174369155}}\n* The Bravest of the Brave: The Extraordinary Story of Indian VCs of World War I {{ISBN|9789386141767}}\n* The Indian Army: A Brief History {{ISBN|8190209701}}\n* The Sinking of INS Khukri: Survivor's Stories {{ISBN|9351940993}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[F. N. Billimoria]]\n*[[Yogendra Singh Yadav]]\n*[[Zorawar Chand Bakhshi]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://claudearpi.blogspot.com/2011/12/forty-years-after-general-cardozos.html Forty Years After: General Cardozo's i