{"title_page": "Benny & Joon", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Benny & Joon\n| image          = Benny and joon ver1.jpg\n| image_size     = 215px\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Jeremiah S. Chechik]]\n| producer       = David Zanuck<br /> Donna Roth\n| writer         = Barry Berman<br />Lesley McNeil\n| starring       = {{plainlist|\n* [[Johnny Depp]]\n* [[Mary Stuart Masterson]]\n* [[Aidan Quinn]]\n* [[Julianne Moore]]\n* [[Oliver Platt]]}}\n| music          = [[Rachel Portman]]\n| cinematography = [[John Schwartzman]]\n| editing        = [[Carol Littleton]]\n| distributor    = [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]]\n| released       = {{Start date|1993|04|23}} \n| runtime        = 98 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = $30 million<ref name=gross>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|title=Warner Bros. tops hot box office 100|last=Klady|first=Leonard|date=January 3, 1994|page=42}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Benny & Joon''''' is a 1993 [[romantic comedy]] film released by [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] about how two eccentric individuals, Sam ([[Johnny Depp]]) and Juniper \"Joon\" ([[Mary Stuart Masterson]]), find each other and fall in love. [[Aidan Quinn]] also stars, and it was directed by [[Jeremiah S. Chechik]].\n\nThe film is perhaps best known for Depp's humorous [[physical comedy]] routines (which are based on [[silent film]] comics [[Buster Keaton]], [[Charlie Chaplin]], and [[Harold Lloyd]]) and for popularizing, in the United States, the song \"[[I'm Gonna Be (500 Miles)]]\" by [[The Proclaimers]].<ref>\nhttp://toponehitwonders.com/pop/im-gonna-be-500-miles-the-proclaimers/</ref>\n''Benny & Joon'' was shot primarily on location in [[Spokane, Washington]], while the train scenes at the beginning were shot near [[Metaline Falls]], Washington.\n\n==Plot==\nBenjamin \"Benny\" Pearl and his mentally ill sister Juniper \"Joon\" Pearl, live together following the accidental death of their parents. Joon joins a poker game at a friend of Benny's named Mike's house and loses a bet that commits Sam, Mike's cousin, to live with the Pearls. Benny is at first angry, but after an evening with Sam at the local diner and then coming home the next day to find Sam has cleaned the house, Benny decides Sam should stay.\n\nJoon aids an illiterate Sam when he is struggling with writing to his mother, and the two go to the local diner where Ruthie is working. She takes them on an errand, and then takes them home. After Ruthie stays for dinner, her car won't start, and Benny drives her home, where they set a dinner date. Meanwhile, left alone, Joon and Sam kiss. Benny and Ruthie have a fun date, but it ends abruptly because Benny wants to get home to Joon. Sam goes to a video store to try to apply for a job there. Benny, Joon, and Sam go to a park where Sam starts doing tricks with his hat, attracting an appreciative crowd. Benny stays at the park to reflect and sends Joon home with Sam, where they make love. Sam then tells Joon he loves her which Joon reciprocates.\n\nWhen Benny makes suggestions to Sam about his comedy routines, Joon becomes agitated and makes Sam explain that he and Joon are romantically involved. An angry Benny throws Sam out, yells at Joon, and shows her a pamphlet about a group home that would be a better home for her. Joon starts hitting Benny and screaming, and he pushes her away. Feeling bad, Benny leaves to get her some tapioca. While Benny is away, Sam arrives. They pack suitcases and get on a bus, but Joon soon begins to hear voices in her head and argues with them, in great distress. Sam tries to soothe her, but she becomes more agitated. The bus is stopped, and two paramedics restrain Joon. When Benny arrives at the hospital, the doctor tells him Joon doesn't want to see him. He finds Sam in the waiting room, and they argue. Sam goes to stay with Ruthie. Meanwhile, Benny begins to feel guilty about his treatment of Joon.\n\nBenny finds Sam, now working at the video store, and asks for his help. They go to the hospital. Benny apologizes to Joon, persuades her to consider getting her own apartment, and tells her that Sam has come back for her. Joon tells the doctor that she would like to try living in her own apartment. Benny and Joon reconcile and Sam and Joon are reunited. Later, Benny brings roses to Ruthie. He takes another bouquet to Joon's apartment but leaves the flowers in the doorway when he sees Sam and Joon are busy making grilled cheese sandwiches with a clothing iron.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Johnny Depp]] as Sam\n* [[Mary Stuart Masterson]] as Juniper \"Joon\" Pearl\n* [[Aidan Quinn]] as Benjamin \"Benny\" Pearl\n* [[Julianne Moore]] as Ruthie\n* [[Oliver Platt]] as Eric\n* [[C.C.H. Pounder]] as Dr. Garvey\n* [[Dan Hedaya]] as Thomas\n* [[Joe Grifasi]] as Mike\n* [[William H. Macy]] as Randy Burch\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n[[Laura Dern]] and [[Woody Harrelson]] were originally cast to play the title roles.<ref name=\"ew930507\"/> Dern changed her mind, and Harrelson quit to take a role in ''[[Indecent Proposal]]''.<ref name=\"ew930507\"/> [[Aidan Quinn]] was brought in at the last minute to replace Harrelson. Unbeknownst to Harrelson, the producer was Donna Roth, the wife of then-[[Paramount Pictures|Paramount Studios]] head [[Joe Roth]]. A lawsuit later ensued with [[Winona Ryder]] who was dating Johnny Depp at the time, and was slated to play Joon after Dern quit. Depp and Ryder broke up, leaving the role of Joon open, which was given to Masterson just days before production began.<ref>{{cite news | last=Saban | first=Stephen | title=The Mighty Quinn | work=[[Movieline]] | page=67| date=October 1994}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n===Critical reception===\n[[Roger Ebert]] gave the film three out of 4 stars.<!-- expand to summarize a little more of the review --><ref name=\"ebert2\">{{cite web| url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19930416/REVIEWS/304160301/1023 |first=Roger |last=Ebert |authorlink= Roger Ebert |title=Benny and Joon | date=April 16, 1993| work=Chicago Sun-Times |accessdate=2011-09-29}}</ref> [[Owen Gleiberman]] gave the film a [[academic grading in the United States|grade of \"B\"]], saying \"the movie is full of absurdist [[wikt:frippery|fripperies]] we're meant to find magically funny; mostly they're just cute (Sam cooking up grilled cheese sandwiches with an iron, a poker game in which a snorkel mask and baseball tickets are used as stakes). Beneath the domesticated surrealism, though, ''Benny & Joon'' becomes genuinely touching\u2013a love story about separation anxiety. Benny, the saintly grease monkey, thinks he has to devote his life to Joon in order to keep her out of an institution. Can he give her the space she needs to fall in love (and then take said space for himself)? You already know the answer, but Quinn and Masterson\u2013now gentle, now sniping\u2013let it play out with tender conviction.\"<ref>{{cite web| url=  http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,306282,00.html | title=Benny & Joon| work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] | authorlink=Owen Gleiberman | first=Owen |last= Gleiberman | date=April 23, 1993|accessdate=2011-09-29}}</ref> [[Janet Maslin]] wrote:<ref>{{cite web| url= https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9F0CE4D6113CF935A25757C0A965958260| title=He's His Sister's Keeper, and What a Job That Is | work=[[The New York Times]] | authorlink=Janet Maslin| first=Janet | last=Maslin| date=April 16, 1993 |accessdate=2011-09-29}}</ref>\n\n<blockquote>In a more realistic film (and to some degree this film recalls ''[[Dominick and Eugene]]'', which also dealt with a hard-working brother taking care of a mentally impaired sibling), troubling issues might well shade the story. But ''Benny and Joon'' succeeds in remaining blithe and sunny, directed by Jeremiah Chechik (''[[National Lampoon's Christmas Vacation]]'') with a commercial liveliness and a suitable sense of the absurd. The film's greatest asset is the obvious conviction of its actors, who never condescend to their roles. Mr. Depp may look nothing like Buster Keaton, but there are times when he genuinely seems to become the Great Stone Face, bringing Keaton's mannerisms sweetly and magically to life. As Mr. Depp and the rest of the film makers surely must have known, an impersonation like that is an all-or-nothing proposition. Ms. Masterson, a remarkably incisive and determined actress, never sentimentalizes Joon despite many ripe opportunities to do exactly that. She remains fierce, funny and persuasive even when the film conveniently soft-pedals the reality of Joon's situation. Mr. Quinn, often in the position of playing straight man to the other two leads, still makes Benny a touchingly sincere and sympathetic figure.</blockquote>\n\nAs of November 2018, ''Benny & Joon'' holds a rating of 71% on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 35 reviews.<ref>{{cite web | title=Benny & Joon | url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/benny_and_joon| website=Rotten Tomatoes | publisher=|accessdate=June 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\nIn spite of its \"commercially improbable story\", the film became a \"[[sleeper hit]]\", evidence of the resurgence of date movies \"after a decade dominated by [[action film]] and [[horror film]]s.\"<ref name=\"ew930507\">{{cite web| url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,306282,00.html | title=A Perfect Mismatch | work=Entertainment Weekly | authorlink=Ryan Murphy (writer) | first=Ryan |last= Murphy | date=May 7, 1993| quote=After a decade dominated by action films, the sleeper success of ''Benny & Joon'' \u2014 an oddball romance starring Masterson and Depp as seemingly ill-matched lovers who find each other a perfect fit \u2014 is the latest evidence that movies made for couples are finding their niche once again. | accessdate=2011-09-29}}</ref> In the first two weeks of a [[limited release]], Benny and Joon grossed $8 million. In its domestic box office total reached over $23.2 million.<ref name=\"boxoff\">{{mojo title|bennyandjoon|Benny & Joon}}</ref> It grossed $7 million overseas for a worldwide total of $30 million.<ref name=gross/>\n\n==Portrayal of schizophrenia==\n[[Roger Ebert]] writes that Joon is \"[[Schizophrenia|schizophrenic]], although the screenplay doesn't ever say the word out loud.\"<ref name=\"ebert\">{{cite book |title=Roger Ebert's Video Companion|first=Roger |last=Ebert |page=69}}</ref>\nDavid J. Robinson remarks that \"More convincing features of schizophrenia (undifferentiated type) soon follow. We are told that Joon experiences auditory hallucinations, does well with a stable routine, and takes medication on a daily basis. Her use of language is one of her most interesting attributes. She uses the last housekeeper's surname (\"Smail\") to refer to anyone who might fill the position, which is how Sam (Johnny Depp) enters her life.\"<ref name=\"robinson\">{{cite book |title=Reel Psychiatry: Movie Portrayals of Psychiatric Conditions|first=David J|last=Robinson |page=36}}</ref>  E. Fuller Torrey calls the film \"a beautifully filmed but unrealistic story about a brother who is the sole caretaker of his kid sister, who has schizophrenia. ... While the film addresses such issues as noncompliance with medication and disputes over independent living arrangements, the bad times are never too severe or long-lasting.<ref name=\"torrey\">{{cite book |title=Surviving Schizophrenia:  A Manual for Families, Patients, and Providers|edition=fifth |first=E. Fuller |last=Torrey|page=377|ISBN=978-0-06-084259-8}}</ref>  Reviewers Mick Martin and Marsha Porter remarked \"[Although] most viewers will enjoy this bittersweet comedy ... Folks coping with mental illness in real life will be offended by yet another film in which the problem is sanitized and trivialized\".<ref name=\"martin\">{{cite book |title=Video movie guide 2002 |author=Mick Martin, Marsha Porter|page=87|ISBN=978-0-345-42100-5}}</ref>\n\n==Musical adaptation==\nA stage musical adaptation of the movie premiered at the [[Old Globe Theatre]] in San Diego, California from September 2 to October 22, 2017.<ref>Hebert, James. [https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/entertainment/theater/sd-me-review-globe-20170916-story.html \" 'Benny & Joon' has charm but trips a bit in leap from screen to stage\"] ''San diego Union Tribune'', September 16, 2017</ref> The musical features music by Nolan Gasser, lyrics by Mindi Dickstein, book by Kirsten Guenther, choreography by Scott Rink and direction by Jack Cummings III. The show runs at [[Paper Mill Playhouse]], Millburn, New Jersey from April 4 to May 5, 2019. The Paper Mill production features [[Claybourne Elder]] as Benny, Hannah Elless as Joon and [[Bryce Pinkham]] as Sam.<ref>[https://papermill.org/cast-creative-team-announced-benny-joon/ \" 'Benny & Joon' Cast\"] papermill.org, retrieved April 14, 2019</ref><ref>Gans, Andrew. [http://www.playbill.com/article/claybourne-elder-hannah-elless-and-bryce-pinkham-star-in-paper-mills-benny-joon-musical-opening-april-14# \"Claybourne Elder, Hannah Elless, and Bryce Pinkham Star in Paper Mill\u2019s 'Benny & Joon' Musical, Opening April 14\"] Playbill, April 14, 2019</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\n{{Anchor|Awards}} \nAlthough the film didn't win any awards, actor [[Johnny Depp]] gained his second Golden Globe Award nomination.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Nomination\n! Category\n! Person\n|-\n| [[Golden Globe Award|Golden Globe]] \n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor - Motion Picture Musical or Comedy|Best Actor - Comedy Movie]]\n| [[Johnny Depp]]\n|-\n| [[MTV Movie Awards|MTV Movie Award]] \n| Best Comedic Performance\n| Johnny Depp\n|-\n| MTV Movie Award\n| Best On-Screen Duo\n| Johnny Depp and [[Mary Stuart Masterson]]\n|-\n| MTV Movie Award \n| Best Movie Song\n| [[The Proclaimers]] - [[I'm Gonna Be (500 Miles)]]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{commons cat}}\n* {{IMDb title|0106387|Benny & Joon}}\n* {{Amg movie|4829|Benny & Joon}}\n* {{mojo title|bennyandjoon|Benny & Joon}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|benny_and_joon|Benny & Joon}}\n\n{{Jeremiah S. Chechik}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Benny and Joon}}\n[[Category:1993 films]]\n[[Category:1990s romantic comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American romantic comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Jeremiah S. Chechik]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Rachel Portman]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer films]]\n[[Category:Films about psychiatry]]\n[[Category:Mental illness in fiction]]\n[[Category:Schizophrenia]]\n[[Category:Fictional portrayals of schizophrenia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Benny & Joon\n| image          = Benny and joon ver1.jpg\n| image_size     = 215px\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Jeremiah S. Chechik]]\n| producer       = David Zanuck<br /> Donna Roth\n| writer         = Barry Berman<br />Lesley McNeil\n| starring       = {{plainlist|\n* [[Johnny Depp]]\n* [[Mary Stuart Masterson]]\n* [[Aidan Quinn]]\n* [[Julianne Moore]]\n* [[Oliver Platt]]}}\n| music          = [[Rachel Portman]]\n| cinematography = [[John Schwartzman]]\n| editing        = [[Carol Littleton]]\n| distributor    = [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]]\n| released       = {{Start date|1993|04|23}} \n| runtime        = 98 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = $30 million<ref name=gross>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|title=Warner Bros. tops hot box office 100|last=Klady|first=Leonard|date=January 3, 1994|page=42}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Benny & Joon''''' is a 1993 [[romantic comedy]] film released by [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] about how two eccentric individuals, Sam ([[Johnny Depp]]) and Juniper \"Joon\" ([[Mary Stuart Masterson]]), find each other and fall in love. [[Aidan Quinn]] also stars, and it was directed by [[Jeremiah S. Chechik]].\n\nThe film is perhaps best known for Depp's humorous [[physical comedy]] routines (which are based on [[silent film]] comics [[Buster Keaton]], [[Charlie Chaplin]], and [[Harold Lloyd]]) and for popularizing, in the United States, the song \"[[I'm Gonna Be (500 Miles)]]\" by [[The Proclaimers]].<ref>\nhttp://toponehitwonders.com/pop/im-gonna-be-500-miles-the-proclaimers/</ref>\n''Benny & Joon'' was shot primarily on location in [[Spokane, Washington]], while the train scenes at the beginning were shot near [[Metaline Falls]], Washington.\n\n==Plot==\nBenjamin \"Benny\" Pearl and his mentally ill sister Juniper \"Joon\" Pearl, live together following the accidental death of their parents. Joon joins a poker game at a friend of Benny's named Mike's house and loses a bet that commits Sam, Mike's cousin, to live with the Pearls. Benny is at first angry, but after an evening with Sam at the local diner and then coming home the next day to find Sam has cleaned the house, Benny decides Sam should stay.\n\nJoon aids an illiterate Sam when he is struggling with writing to his mother, and the two go to the local diner where Ruthie is working. She takes them on an errand, and then takes them home. After Ruthie stays for dinner, her car won't start, and Benny drives her home, where they set a dinner date. Meanwhile, left alone, Joon and Sam kiss. Benny and Ruthie have a fun date, but it ends abruptly because Benny wants to get home to Joon. Sam goes to a video store to try and apply for a job there. Benny, Joon, and Sam go to a park where Sam starts doing tricks with his hat, attracting an appreciative crowd. Benny stays at the park to reflect and sends Joon home with Sam, where they make love. Sam then tells Joon he loves her which Joon reciprocates.\n\nWhen Benny makes suggestions to Sam about his comedy routines, Joon becomes agitated and makes Sam explain that he and Joon are romantically involved. An angry Benny throws Sam out, yells at Joon, and shows her a pamphlet about a group home that would be a better home for her. Joon starts hitting Benny and screaming, and he pushes her away. Feeling bad, Benny leaves to get her some tapioca. While Benny is away, Sam arrives. They pack suitcases and get on a bus, but Joon soon begins to hear voices in her head and argues with them, in great distress. Sam tries to soothe her, but she becomes more agitated. The bus is stopped, and two paramedics restrain Joon. When Benny arrives at the hospital, the doctor tells him Joon doesn't want to see him. He finds Sam in the waiting room, and they argue. Sam goes to stay with Ruthie. Meanwhile, Benny begins to feel guilty about his treatment of Joon.\n\nBenny finds Sam, now working at the video store, and asks for his help. They go to the hospital. Benny apologizes to Joon, persuades her to consider getting her own apartment, and tells her that Sam has come back for her. Joon tells the doctor that she would like to try living in her own apartment. Benny and Joon reconcile and Sam and Joon are reunited. Later, Benny brings roses to Ruthie. He takes another bouquet to Joon's apartment but leaves the flowers in the doorway when he sees Sam and Joon are busy making grilled cheese sandwiches with a clothing iron.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Johnny Depp]] as Sam\n* [[Mary Stuart Masterson]] as Juniper \"Joon\" Pearl\n* [[Aidan Quinn]] as Benjamin \"Benny\" Pearl\n* [[Julianne Moore]] as Ruthie\n* [[Oliver Platt]] as Eric\n* [[C.C.H. Pounder]] as Dr. Garvey\n* [[Dan Hedaya]] as Thomas\n* [[Joe Grifasi]] as Mike\n* [[William H. Macy]] as Randy Burch\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n[[Laura Dern]] and [[Woody Harrelson]] were originally cast to play the title roles.<ref name=\"ew930507\"/> Dern changed her mind, and Harrelson quit to take a role in ''[[Indecent Proposal]]''.<ref name=\"ew930507\"/> [[Aidan Quinn]] was brought in at the last minute to replace Harrelson. Unbeknownst to Harrelson, the producer was Donna Roth, the wife of then-[[Paramount Pictures|Paramount Studios]] head [[Joe Roth]]. A lawsuit later ensued with [[Winona Ryder]] who was dating Johnny Depp at the time, and was slated to play Joon after Dern quit. Depp and Ryder broke up, leaving the role of Joon open, which was given to Masterson just days before production began.<ref>{{cite news | last=Saban | first=Stephen | title=The Mighty Quinn | work=[[Movieline]] | page=67| date=October 1994}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n===Critical reception===\n[[Roger Ebert]] gave the film three out of 4 stars.<!-- expand to summarize a little more of the review --><ref name=\"ebert2\">{{cite web| url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19930416/REVIEWS/304160301/1023 |first=Roger |last=Ebert |authorlink= Roger Ebert |title=Benny and Joon | date=April 16, 1993| work=Chicago Sun-Times |accessdate=2011-09-29}}</ref> [[Owen Gleiberman]] gave the film a [[academic grading in the United States|grade of \"B\"]], saying \"the movie is full of absurdist [[wikt:frippery|fripperies]] we're meant to find magically funny; mostly they're just cute (Sam cooking up grilled cheese sandwiches with an iron, a poker game in which a snorkel mask and baseball tickets are used as stakes). Beneath the domesticated surrealism, though, ''Benny & Joon'' becomes genuinely touching\u2013a love story about separation anxiety. Benny, the saintly grease monkey, thinks he has to devote his life to Joon in order to keep her out of an institution. Can he give her the space she needs to fall in love (and then take said space for himself)? You already know the answer, but Quinn and Masterson\u2013now gentle, now sniping\u2013let it play out with tender conviction.\"<ref>{{cite web| url=  http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,306282,00.html | title=Benny & Joon| work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] | authorlink=Owen Gleiberman | first=Owen |last= Gleiberman | date=April 23, 1993|accessdate=2011-09-29}}</ref> [[Janet Maslin]] wrote:<ref>{{cite web| url= https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9F0CE4D6113CF935A25757C0A965958260| title=He's His Sister's Keeper, and What a Job That Is | work=[[The New York Times]] | authorlink=Janet Maslin| first=Janet | last=Maslin| date=April 16, 1993 |accessdate=2011-09-29}}</ref>\n\n<blockquote>In a more realistic film (and to some degree this film recalls ''[[Dominick and Eugene]]'', which also dealt with a hard-working brother taking care of a mentally impaired sibling), troubling issues might well shade the story. But ''Benny and Joon'' succeeds in remaining blithe and sunny, directed by Jeremiah Chechik (''[[National Lampoon's Christmas Vacation]]'') with a commercial liveliness and a suitable sense of the absurd. The film's greatest asset is the obvious conviction of its actors, who never condescend to their roles. Mr. Depp may look nothing like Buster Keaton, but there are times when he genuinely seems to become the Great Stone Face, bringing Keaton's mannerisms sweetly and magically to life. As Mr. Depp and the rest of the film makers surely must have known, an impersonation like that is an all-or-nothing proposition. Ms. Masterson, a remarkably incisive and determined actress, never sentimentalizes Joon despite many ripe opportunities to do exactly that. She remains fierce, funny and persuasive even when the film conveniently soft-pedals the reality of Joon's situation. Mr. Quinn, often in the position of playing straight man to the other two leads, still makes Benny a touchingly sincere and sympathetic figure.</blockquote>\n\nAs of November 2018, ''Benny & Joon'' holds a rating of 71% on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 35 reviews.<ref>{{cite web | title=Benny & Joon | url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/benny_and_joon| website=Rotten Tomatoes | publisher=|accessdate=June 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\nIn spite of its \"commercially improbable story\", the film became a \"[[sleeper hit]]\", evidence of the resurgence of date movies \"after a decade dominated by [[action film]] and [[horror film]]s.\"<ref name=\"ew930507\">{{cite web| url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,306282,00.html | title=A Perfect Mismatch | work=Entertainment Weekly | authorlink=Ryan Murphy (writer) | first=Ryan |last= Murphy | date=May 7, 1993| quote=After a decade dominated by action films, the sleeper success of ''Benny & Joon'' \u2014 an oddball romance starring Masterson and Depp as seemingly ill-matched lovers who find each other a perfect fit \u2014 is the latest evidence that movies made for couples are finding their niche once again. | accessdate=2011-09-29}}</ref> In the first two weeks of a [[limited release]], Benny and Joon grossed $8 million. In its domestic box office total reached over $23.2 million.<ref name=\"boxoff\">{{mojo title|bennyandjoon|Benny & Joon}}</ref> It grossed $7 million overseas for a worldwide total of $30 million.<ref name=gross/>\n\n==Portrayal of schizophrenia==\n[[Roger Ebert]] writes that Joon is \"[[Schizophrenia|schizophrenic]], although the screenplay doesn't ever say the word out loud.\"<ref name=\"ebert\">{{cite book |title=Roger Ebert's Video Companion|first=Roger |last=Ebert |page=69}}</ref>\nDavid J. Robinson remarks that \"More convincing features of schizophrenia (undifferentiated type) soon follow. We are told that Joon experiences auditory hallucinations, does well with a stable routine, and takes medication on a daily basis. Her use of language is one of her most interesting attributes. She uses the last housekeeper's surname (\"Smail\") to refer to anyone who might fill the position, which is how Sam (Johnny Depp) enters her life.\"<ref name=\"robinson\">{{cite book |title=Reel Psychiatry: Movie Portrayals of Psychiatric Conditions|first=David J|last=Robinson |page=36}}</ref>  E. Fuller Torrey calls the film \"a beautifully filmed but unrealistic story about a brother who is the sole caretaker of his kid sister, who has schizophrenia. ... While the film addresses such issues as noncompliance with medication and disputes over independent living arrangements, the bad times are never too severe or long-lasting.<ref name=\"torrey\">{{cite book |title=Surviving Schizophrenia:  A Manual for Families, Patients, and Providers|edition=fifth |first=E. Fuller |last=Torrey|page=377|ISBN=978-0-06-084259-8}}</ref>  Reviewers Mick Martin and Marsha Porter remarked \"[Although] most viewers will enjoy this bittersweet comedy ... Folks coping with mental illness in real life will be offended by yet another film in which the problem is sanitized and trivialized\".<ref name=\"martin\">{{cite book |title=Video movie guide 2002 |author=Mick Martin, Marsha Porter|page=87|ISBN=978-0-345-42100-5}}</ref>\n\n==Musical adaptation==\nA stage musical adaptation of the movie premiered at the [[Old Globe Theatre]] in San Diego, California from September 2 to October 22, 2017.<ref>Hebert, James. [https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/entertainment/theater/sd-me-review-globe-20170916-story.html \" 'Benny & Joon' has charm but trips a bit in leap from screen to stage\"] ''San diego Union Tribune'', September 16, 2017</ref> The musical features music by Nolan Gasser, lyrics by Mindi Dickstein, book by Kirsten Guenther, choreography by Scott Rink and direction by Jack Cummings III. The show runs at [[Paper Mill Playhouse]], Millburn, New Jersey from April 4 to May 5, 2019. The Paper Mill production features [[Claybourne Elder]] as Benny, Hannah Elless as Joon and [[Bryce Pinkham]] as Sam.<ref>[https://papermill.org/cast-creative-team-announced-benny-joon/ \" 'Benny & Joon' Cast\"] papermill.org, retrieved April 14, 2019</ref><ref>Gans, Andrew. [http://www.playbill.com/article/claybourne-elder-hannah-elless-and-bryce-pinkham-star-in-paper-mills-benny-joon-musical-opening-april-14# \"Claybourne Elder, Hannah Elless, and Bryce Pinkham Star in Paper Mill\u2019s 'Benny & Joon' Musical, Opening April 14\"] Playbill, April 14, 2019</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\n{{Anchor|Awards}} \nAlthough the film didn't win any awards, actor [[Johnny Depp]] gained his second Golden Globe Award nomination.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Nomination\n! Category\n! Person\n|-\n| [[Golden Globe Award|Golden Globe]] \n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor - Motion Picture Musical or Comedy|Best Actor - Comedy Movie]]\n| [[Johnny Depp]]\n|-\n| [[MTV Movie Awards|MTV Movie Award]] \n| Best Comedic Performance\n| Johnny Depp\n|-\n| MTV Movie Award\n| Best On-Screen Duo\n| Johnny Depp and [[Mary Stuart Masterson]]\n|-\n| MTV Movie Award \n| Best Movie Song\n| [[The Proclaimers]] - [[I'm Gonna Be (500 Miles)]]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{commons cat}}\n* {{IMDb title|0106387|Benny & Joon}}\n* {{Amg movie|4829|Benny & Joon}}\n* {{mojo title|bennyandjoon|Benny & Joon}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|benny_and_joon|Benny & Joon}}\n\n{{Jeremiah S. Chechik}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Benny and Joon}}\n[[Category:1993 films]]\n[[Category:1990s romantic comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American romantic comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Jeremiah S. Chechik]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Rachel Portman]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer films]]\n[[Category:Films about psychiatry]]\n[[Category:Mental illness in fiction]]\n[[Category:Schizophrenia]]\n[[Category:Fictional portrayals of schizophrenia]]\n", "name_user": "Vossron", "label": "safe", "comment": "\"try to\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Benny_%26_Joon"}
{"title_page": "Kath Pettingill", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian criminal}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox criminal\n| name   = Kathleen Pettingill\n| image_name     =\n| image_size     =\n| image_caption  = Kathleen Pettingill, as seen on the cover of her biography, ''The Matriarch: The Kathy Pettingill Story''\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|27 March 1935|df=y}}\n| birth_place =\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| alias          = Granny Evil\n| charge         =\n| conviction     = [[Drug trafficking]]\n| conviction_penalty        =\n| conviction_status         =\n| occupation     = Former [[Procuring (prostitution)|brothel owner]]\n| spouse         =\n| parents        =\n| children       = 10<ref name=clean/>\n}}\n'''Kathleen Pettingill''' (born 27 March, 1935) is the [[matriarch]] of the [[Melbourne]] criminal family, the [[Pettingill family]].\n\n==Family==\nPettingill's 10 children are:\n\n(with Dennis Ryan)\n*[[Dennis Allen (criminal)|Dennis Bruce Allen]] (1951\u20131987) - a drug dealer, jailed for rape in 1973 and died in 1987 of a heart attack while in custody awaiting trial for murder.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2002/05/02/1019441412194.html |title=Brace for more gangland shootings, police warn |author1=Munroe, Ian |author2=Butcher, Steve |date=3 May 2002 |work=[[The Age]] |accessdate=2 July 2010}}</ref>\n*Peter Allen (born 1953) - convicted of armed robbery, who was once Victoria's most dangerous man and spent 28 years in jail.<ref name=\"clean\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/general/coming-clean/2005/09/30/1127804661698.html |title=Coming clean |date=1 October 2005 |work=[[The Age]] |accessdate=2 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n(with William George \"Billy\" Peirce (died 1968))\n*Vicki Brooks (born 1954; n\u00e9e Pettingill) - gave evidence against the family in the Walsh Street trial and subsequently went into witness protection.\n*\"Shelley\" (born 1956) - real name unknown. Given up for adoption and reestablished contact with Pettingill in 1989.<ref name=\"Matriarch\">''The Matriarch'' {{ISBN|978-0732908546}}</ref>\n*\"Stephen\" (born 1957) - real name unknown. Given up for adoption and reestablished contact with Pettingill in 1989.<ref name=Matriarch/>\n*[[Victor Peirce|Victor George Peirce]] (1958\u20132002) - acquitted of the 1988 [[Walsh Street police shootings]] and was killed in 2002.\n*Lex Peirce (born 1960) - has a minor criminal record.<ref name=clean/>\n*\"David\" (born 1961) - real name unknown. Given up for adoption and whereabouts currently unknown.<ref name=Matriarch/>\n\n(with Jimmy Pettingill (died 1972))\n*Jamie Pettingill (1963\u20131985) - died of a heroin overdose aged 21.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2002/05/02/1019441413044.html |title=Crime world loses one of its finest |date=3 May 2002 |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |accessdate=2 July 2010}}</ref>\n*Trevor Pettingill (born 1965) - acquitted of the 1988 Walsh Street police shootings, who has multiple convictions for firearms and drug-related offences and has served several jail terms.<ref name=jamie/> He has been described as a \"career criminal\".<ref name=\"jamie\">{{Cite web |url=http://news.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=1054865 |title=Melbourne crime figure's son guilty |date=20 May 2010 |work=[[Ninemsn]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110224222629/http://news.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=1054865 |archivedate=24 February 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nPettingill first worked in a bar, and having herself been a [[prostitute]],<ref>{{Cite book|last=Tame|first=Adrian|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5_eURuovsFMC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=prostitute|title=The Matriarch: The Kathy Pettingill Story|publisher=Pan Macmillan|year=1996|isbn=978-0-7329-0854-6|pages=58, 60|accessdate=2 July 2010}}</ref> she went on to run brothels.<ref name=\"clean\" /> She lived with her children in the [[Richmond, Victoria|Richmond]] area of Melbourne, and a number of her sons were sent to the [[Melbourne Youth Justice Centre|Turana Boys' Home]]. \n\nPettingill has a [[glass eye]] to replace the one she lost after being shot in 1978 by Kim Nelson and Keryn Thompson. The bullet passed through a closed door at the Collingwood [[Housing Commission of Victoria]] flats as she and her son, Dennis Allen, attempted to repay a $300 debt on behalf of her daughter, Vicky Brooks.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Shand|first=Adam|title=Big Shots|publisher=Viking Books|year=2007|isbn=978-0-670-04071-1|page=}}</ref>{{Page needed|date=September 2010}}\n\n== In popular culture ==\nA [[biography]] of her life, ''The Matriarch: The Kathy Pettingill Story,'' was written by Adrian Tame and published in 1996. As of 2007, Pettingill was living in [[Venus Bay, Victoria|Venus Bay]], [[Gippsland]], Victoria.<ref name=\"bingo\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/bingo-dogs-numbers-up/story-e6frf7kx-1111113712680 |title=Bingo dogs' number's up |author=Tame, Adrian |date=10 June 2007 |work=[[Herald Sun]] |accessdate=2 July 2010}}</ref>\n\nA fictionalised version of her appears in the 2010 film ''[[Animal Kingdom (film)|Animal Kingdom]]'', in which she is portrayed by [[Jacki Weaver]], who was nominated for an [[Academy Award]] for the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]] for her performance.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist | 30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.heraldsun.news.com.au/common/story_page/0,5478,16784895%255E2862,00.html Father's fury at Walsh St admission] -  [[Herald Sun]], 2 October 2005\n\n{{Pettingill family}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pettingill, Kath}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian brothel owners and madams]]\n[[Category:Australian drug traffickers]]\n[[Category:Australian female prostitutes]]\n[[Category:Australian criminals]]\n[[Category:Criminals from Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Pettingill family|Kath]]\n[[Category:Female organized crime figures]]\n[[Category:Australian people with disabilities]]\n\n\n{{AUS-crime-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Australian criminal}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox criminal\n| name   = Kathleen Pettingill\n| image_name     =\n| image_size     =\n| image_caption  = Kathleen Pettingill, as seen on the cover of her biography, ''The Matriarch: The Kathy Pettingill Story''\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|27 March 1935|df=y}}\n| birth_place =\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| alias          = Granny Evil\n| charge         =\n| conviction     = [[Drug trafficking]]\n| conviction_penalty        =\n| conviction_status         =\n| occupation     = Former [[Procuring (prostitution)|brothel owner]]\n| spouse         =\n| parents        =\n| children       = 10<ref name=clean/>\n}}\n'''Kathleen Pettingill''' (born 27 March, 1935) is the [[matriarch]] of the [[Melbourne]] criminal family, the [[Pettingill family]].\n\n==Family==\nPettingill's 10 children are:\n\n(with Dennis Ryan)\n*[[Dennis Allen (criminal)|Dennis Bruce Allen]] (1951\u20131987) - a drug dealer, jailed for rape in 1973 and died in 1987 of a heart attack while in custody awaiting trial for murder.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2002/05/02/1019441412194.html |title=Brace for more gangland shootings, police warn |author1=Munroe, Ian |author2=Butcher, Steve |date=3 May 2002 |work=[[The Age]] |accessdate=2 July 2010}}</ref>\n*Peter Allen (born 1953) - convicted of armed robbery, who was once Victoria's most dangerous man and spent 28 years in jail.<ref name=\"clean\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/general/coming-clean/2005/09/30/1127804661698.html |title=Coming clean |date=1 October 2005 |work=[[The Age]] |accessdate=2 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n(with William George \"Billy\" Peirce (died 1968))\n*Vicki Brooks (born 1954; nee Pettingill) - gave evidence against the family in the Walsh Street trial and subsequently went into witness protection.\n*\"Shelley\" (born 1956) - real name unknown. Given up for adoption and reestablished contact with Pettingill in 1989.<ref name=\"Matriarch\">''The Matriarch'' {{ISBN|978-0732908546}}</ref>\n*\"Stephen\" (born 1957) - real name unknown. Given up for adoption and reestablished contact with Pettingill in 1989.<ref name=Matriarch/>\n*[[Victor Peirce|Victor George Peirce]] (1958\u20132002) - acquitted of the 1988 [[Walsh Street police shootings]] and was killed in 2002.\n*Lex Peirce (born 1960) - has a minor criminal record.<ref name=clean/>\n*\"David\" (born 1961) - real name unknown. Given up for adoption and whereabouts currently unknown.<ref name=Matriarch/>\n\n(with Jimmy Pettingill (died 1972))\n*Jamie Pettingill (1963\u20131985) - died of a heroin overdose aged 21.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2002/05/02/1019441413044.html |title=Crime world loses one of its finest |date=3 May 2002 |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |accessdate=2 July 2010}}</ref>\n*Trevor Pettingill (born 1965) - acquitted of the 1988 Walsh Street police shootings, who has multiple convictions for firearms and drug-related offences and has served several jail terms.<ref name=jamie/> He has been described as a \"career criminal\".<ref name=\"jamie\">{{Cite web |url=http://news.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=1054865 |title=Melbourne crime figure's son guilty |date=20 May 2010 |work=[[Ninemsn]] |accessdate=2 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110224222629/http://news.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=1054865 |archivedate=24 February 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nPettingill first worked in a bar, and having herself been a [[prostitute]],<ref>{{Cite book|last=Tame|first=Adrian|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5_eURuovsFMC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=prostitute|title=The Matriarch: The Kathy Pettingill Story|publisher=Pan Macmillan|year=1996|isbn=978-0-7329-0854-6|pages=58, 60|accessdate=2 July 2010}}</ref> she went on to run brothels.<ref name=\"clean\" /> She lived with her children in the [[Richmond, Victoria|Richmond]] area of Melbourne, and a number of her sons were sent to the [[Melbourne Youth Justice Centre|Turana Boys' Home]]. \n\nPettingill has a [[glass eye]] to replace the one she lost after being shot in 1978 by Kim Nelson and Keryn Thompson. The bullet passed through a closed door at the Collingwood [[Housing Commission of Victoria]] flats as she and her son, Dennis Allen, attempted to repay a $300 debt on behalf of her daughter, Vicky Brooks.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Shand|first=Adam|title=Big Shots|publisher=Viking Books|year=2007|isbn=978-0-670-04071-1|page=}}</ref>{{Page needed|date=September 2010}}\n\n== In popular culture ==\nA [[biography]] of her life, ''The Matriarch: The Kathy Pettingill Story,'' was written by Adrian Tame and published in 1996. As of 2007, Pettingill was living in [[Venus Bay, Victoria|Venus Bay]], [[Gippsland]], Victoria.<ref name=\"bingo\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/bingo-dogs-numbers-up/story-e6frf7kx-1111113712680 |title=Bingo dogs' number's up |author=Tame, Adrian |date=10 June 2007 |work=[[Herald Sun]] |accessdate=2 July 2010}}</ref>\n\nA fictionalised version of her appears in the 2010 film ''[[Animal Kingdom (film)|Animal Kingdom]]'', in which she is portrayed by [[Jacki Weaver]], who was nominated for an [[Academy Award]] for the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]] for her performance.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist | 30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.heraldsun.news.com.au/common/story_page/0,5478,16784895%255E2862,00.html Father's fury at Walsh St admission] -  [[Herald Sun]], 2 October 2005\n\n{{Pettingill family}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pettingill, Kath}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian brothel owners and madams]]\n[[Category:Australian drug traffickers]]\n[[Category:Australian female prostitutes]]\n[[Category:Australian criminals]]\n[[Category:Criminals from Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Pettingill family|Kath]]\n[[Category:Female organized crime figures]]\n[[Category:Australian people with disabilities]]\n\n\n{{AUS-crime-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFamily:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: nee \u2192  n\u00e9e", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kath_Pettingill"}
{"title_page": "Tilly Devine", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian criminal}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2011}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox person \n| name =Tilly Devine \n| image = Tilly Devine 1925.jpg\n| image_upright = 1.6\n| alt = \n| caption = Tilly Devine in 1925 \n| birth_name =Matilda Mary Twiss \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1900|09|30|df=y}} \n| birth_place = [[Camberwell]], [[London]] \n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1970|11|24|1900|09|30|df=y}}  \n| death_place = [[Concord Repatriation General Hospital|Concord Repatriation Hospital]], Sydney\n| burial_place = [[Eastern Suburbs Memorial Park]] \n| nationality = [[English Australian]] \n| other_names = ''Queen of Woolloomooloo''<ref name=smh-obit/> \n| occupation = \n| years_active = ''[[circa]]'' 1920s{{spaced endash}} 1950s \n| known_for = [[Razor gang]]s, [[Madam#Alternate use|madam]], [[sly-grog shop|sly-grog]] supply \n| notable_works =\n| criminal_charge    =  <!-- Criminality parameters should be supported with citations from reliable sources -->\n| criminal_penalty   = \n| criminal_status    =  \n| spouse             = {{plainlist|\n*James Edward \"Jim\" Devine {{small|(m. 1917, div. 1944)}}\n*Eric John Parsons {{small|(m. 1945, dec'd. 1958)}} }}\n}}\n'''Matilda Mary Devine''' (n\u00e9e '''Twiss''', 8 September 1900{{spaced ndash}}24 November 1970), known as '''Tilly Devine''', was an [[English Australian]] organised crime boss. She was involved in a wide range of activities, including [[sly-grog shop|sly-grog]], [[razor gang]]s, and prostitution, and became a famous folk figure in Sydney during the interwar years.\n\n==Early life==\nDevine was born the daughter of bricklayer Edward Twiss, and Alice Twiss (n\u00e9e Tubb) at 57 Hollington Street, [[Camberwell]], London in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{harvnb|Writer|2001|p=23}}</ref><ref>Census 1901, Camberwell, St George, District 5, page 12</ref> At 16 she married an Australian serviceman, '''James (Jim) Edward Devine''', (born  [[Brunswick, Victoria]], 1892, died [[Melbourne]], 1966), on 12 April 1917 at the Sacred Heart Church, Camberwell, London. The couple had one son, born at Camberwell in 1919.\n\nHer career in prostitution began when she was a teenager and continued after she was married. She and many English women were usually found soliciting on the wide footpaths on The Strand, at night. From 1915 onwards to 1919, she spent time at Bow Street Court and Lock Up for prostitution, theft and assault.\n\nWhen Jim returned to Australia she followed him back on the bride ship ''Waimana'', arriving in Sydney on 13 January 1920. Her son stayed in London and was brought up by her parents.<ref name= bio>{{cite book |first1=Judith |last1=Allen |first2=Baiba |last2=Irving |title= Devine, Matilda (Mary) (1900 - 1970) |work=[[Australian Dictionary of Biography]] |chapter-url= http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A080318b.htm |publisher=Australian National University |year=2011 |accessdate= 9 March 2008|chapter=Devine, Matilda Mary (Tilly) (1900\u20131970) }}</ref>  Both Tilly and Jim Devine rapidly became prominent illegal narcotics dealers, brothel owners and crime gangs members in the Sydney criminal milieu.\n\n==Criminal career==\n\nDevine became infamous in Sydney, initially as a prostitute, then later as a brothel madam and organised crime entrepreneur. The NSW Vagrancy Act 1905 prohibited men from running brothels; it did nothing to stop women with criminal gangs' support and bribes to the police from running criminal enterprises. Historian Larry Writer has noted that the Devines ran diversified operations. Elite \"call girls\" were available for politicians, businessmen and overseas guests of significance, while \"tenement girls\" were young working-class women who resorted to casual prostitution to supplement their drug spendings, clothings and meagre earnings during times of Australian criminal and narcotic culture, absence of a comprehensive welfare state and unemployment. Older female prostitutes, \"boat girls\", catered to itinerant sailors or working class-men. Devine does not seem to have run similar operations for the gay sex market during this time because she believed it was not right.<ref>{{harvnb|Writer|2009|p=200}}</ref>\n\nDevine's wealth was legendary, although it was all earned from crime. She owned much real estate in Sydney, many luxury cars, looted gold and diamond jewellery and travelled by ship in first class staterooms. Much of her wealth was also used to pay bribes to the police sectors, and fines for her criminal convictions that spanned fifty years. Devine faced numerous court summons and was convicted on 204 occasions during her long criminal career, and served many gaol sentences in New South Wales gaols, mainly for prostitution, violent assault, affray and attempted murder. She was known to the police to be of a violent nature and was known to use firearms.\n\n==Marriage to Jim Devine ==\n[[File:James Devine 1939.jpg|thumb|Jim Devine in 1939]]\nJim Devine was an ex-serviceman and shearer, who was a violent 'stand-over' man, a convicted thief, a pimp, drug dealer, vicious thug and gunman. He was also an alcoholic. Devine committed a number of high-profile murders in Sydney between 1929 and 1931: notably, the murder of criminal George Leonard \"Gregory\" Gaffney on 17 July 1929,<ref>{{cite news |work=Sydney Morning Herald |title=Funeral Notice. George Leonard Gaffney|date=20 July 1929 |page=13 }}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Doyle|2009|p=237}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |work=Sydney Morning Herald |title=GANG WAR. GUN DUEL AT MAROUBRA. Man Fatally Shot., Others Wounded|date=19 July 1929 |page=13 }}</ref> secondly, as an accessory to the murder of [[Barney Dalton]] <ref>{{cite news |work=Sydney Morning Herald |title=Death Notice|date=12 November 1929 |first=Barney |last=Dalton |page=10 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |work=Sydney Morning Herald |title=Man Shot Dead. Underworld Warfare|date=11 November 1929 |page=11 }}</ref> on 9 November 1929 (with infamous Sydney gangster and assassin, Francis Donald \"Frankie\" Green) and, thirdly, the accidental shooting of taxi driver, Frederick Herbert Moffitt on 16 June 1931.<ref>{{cite news |work=Sydney Morning Herald |title=MAROUBRA MURDER. James Devine Charged. Counsel's Protest in Court|date=19 June 1931 |page=14 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |work=Sydney Morning Herald |title=Funeral Notice. Frederick Herbert Moffitt |date=18 June 1931 |page=7 }}</ref> Although he was charged with murder on more than one occasion, he was always acquitted, successfully arguing [[Self-defence (Australia)|self defence]]. He shot and killed Gaffney and Moffitt outside his and Tilly's [[Maroubra, New South Wales|Maroubra]] residence.<ref>{{harvnb|Blaikie|1980|p= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |work=Sydney Morning Herald |title=DEVINE Acquitted on murder charge. MAROUBRA SHOOTING|date=14 September 1929 |page=14 }}</ref>\n\nTilly and Jim Devine's marriage was marred by domestic violence. On 9 January 1931, Jim was charged at Central Police Court with the attempted murder of his wife after a heated argument at their Maroubra home. As Tilly ran out of the house, Jim fired a number of shots at her in a similar way to the murder of George Leonard Gaffney in 1929. Tilly escaped unscathed, the only damage being one of her brand new stilettos - the left one. Their terrified neighbours called the police resulting in Jim being arrested and charged over the incident. He was later acquitted, on 16 January 1931, because Tilly refused to testify.<ref>{{cite news |work=Sydney Morning Herald |title='HUSBAND CHARGED'. 'Alleged Attempted Murder|date=10 January 1931 |page=8 }}</ref> The Devines separated in the early 1940s and were finally divorced in January 1944.<ref>{{cite news |work=Sydney Morning Herald |title=Devine divorce hearing|date=31 March 1943 |page=11 }}</ref> Shortly after Tilly separated from Jim, long time criminal associate, Donald Alexander Kenney (1906-1963), known as 'Skinny Kenney', became Tilly's lover and stand-over man.<ref>{{cite news |work=The Wingham Chronicle And Manning River Observer |title=Skinny Kenny |date=5 October 1943}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Skinny Kenny |work=Truth |location=Sydney |date=5 July 1942 |page=17 }}</ref>\n\n==Second marriage==\n\nDevine married for the second time on 19 May 1945 to ex-seaman and returned serviceman '''Eric John Parsons''' (born [[Melbourne]] 1901, died [[Sydney]] 1958).<ref>{{cite news |work=Sydney Morning Herald |title=Death Notice: Eric John Parsons |date=24 November 1958 }}</ref>\n\nTilly famously shot Parsons in the leg after an argument only months before they were married. This shooting occurred at her other Sydney residence: 191 Palmer Street, [[Darlinghurst]]. The house was almost opposite the notorious ''Tradesman's Arms Hotel''. It was at this hotel that Devine met Eric Parsons.<ref>{{cite news |work=Sydney Morning Herald |date=21 February 1945 |page=5 |title=Tilly Devine Charged. Shooting Alleged }}</ref> She was arrested by police and charged with the shooting,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article2617043 |work=[[The Canberra Times]] |title=Tilly Devine On Attempted Murder Charge in Sydney |page=3 |date=21 February 1945 |publisher=National Library of Australia |accessdate=28 August 2011}}</ref> but was acquitted at trial on 31 March 1945.<ref>{{cite news |work=Sydney Morning Herald |date=30 March 1945 |page=4 |title=Tilly Devine Discharged }}</ref> They were happily married for 13 years until Eric Parsons died of cancer on 22 November 1958.\n\nFor over 30 years, Devine lived at 335 Malabar Road, [[Maroubra, New South Wales|Maroubra]] in Sydney's south-eastern suburbs. A number of homicides were committed at this residence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article22903708|title=Guns Blazed in Sydney's Underworld!|date=8 July 1950|pages=26|accessdate=5 November 2017|via=Trove}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |work=Sydney Morning Herald |date=11 July 1931  |title=Desperate Gun Duel. \"Divine's Alleged Confession at Moffitt Inquest\" |page=11 |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article16792668 |publisher=National Library of Australia }}</ref> The property remained derelict from the 1950s onwards. It was sold in 2009 and the new owner built a new house on the lot.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/wreckers-ball-for-notorious-brothelkeepers-home-20090717-do93.html|title=Wrecker's ball for notorious brothel-keeper's home|first=Clancy|last=Yeates|date=18 July 2009|accessdate=5 November 2017|via=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref>\n\n==Decline and death==\nAlthough Devine had been one of Sydney's wealthiest women, by 1955 the Taxation Department ordered her to pay more than \u00a320,000 in unpaid income tax and fines sending her close to bankruptcy.<ref>{{cite news |work=[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]] |location=Melbourne |title=Tilly in 'Ton of Trouble' |date=18 October 1955 |page=5 }}</ref> In 1953 Devine boasted to the media, \"I am a lucky, lucky girl. I have more diamonds than the Queen of England's stowaways - and better ones too!\"<ref>{{harvnb|Blaikie|1980|page=124}}</ref> She sold off her last brothel in Palmer Street, Darlinghurst in 1968, and died two years later.<ref name=\"Writer\">{{harvnb|Writer|2001|p= }}</ref>\n\nDevine was famous for flamboyant acts of generosity, and also for her violent feud with criminal vice rival [[Kate Leigh]]. Devine was charged by the famous Sydney Detective [[Frank Farrell (rugby league)|Frank Farrell]] on many occasions, and their feud lasted for 30 years.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}}\n\nDevine had suffered from chronic bronchitis for 20 years, and died of cancer, aged 70 at the [[Concord Repatriation General Hospital|Concord Repatriation Hospital]] in Sydney on 24 November 1970. Her funeral service was held at the Sacred Heart Catholic Church, Darlinghurst.<ref name=smh-obit>{{cite web|title=Devine, Matilda Mary (Tilly) (1900\u20131970): Obituary|url=http://oa.anu.edu.au/obituary/devine-matilda-mary-tilly-5970/text24395|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=28 August 2011|page=18|date=25 November 1970|via=Obituaries Australia http://oa.anu.edu.au/obituary/devine-matilda-mary-tilly-5970/text24395}}</ref> She was cremated at Botany Crematorium, now known as [[Eastern Suburbs Memorial Park]], on 26 November 1970 with Catholic rites by her married name, Matilda Mary Parsons. She was survived by her son Frederick Ralph (Devine) Twiss (1919\u20131978) and 2 grandchildren.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}} Her funeral service was poorly attended and her death went virtually unnoticed by Sydney's media and population and it was said that very few people openly mourned her death. The only public eulogy offered to Devine was given by the then police commissioner Norman Allan who said: \"She was a villain, but who am I to judge her?\"<ref>{{harvnb|Lipson|Barnao|1992|p=135}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n[[Peter Kenna]] wrote a play called ''The Slaughter of St Teresa\u2019s Day'' (1973 Currency Press),<ref name= slaughter>{{cite web |title=  Fifty Australians - Tilly Devine |publisher= Australian War Memorial |url= http://www.awm.gov.au/fiftyaustralians/15.asp |accessdate= 9 March 2008}}</ref> based on Devine's life.\n\nThe song \"Miss Divine\" from the 1990 [[Icehouse (band)|Icehouse]] album ''[[Code Blue (Icehouse album)|Code Blue]]'' is about Devine.\n\nA popular cafe-nightclub in [[Lyneham, Australian Capital Territory|Lyneham]], [[Canberra]] is called [[Tilley's Devine Cafe|Tilleys Devine Cafe Gallery]]. A wine bar in [[Darlinghurst, New South Wales|Darlinghurst]], [[Sydney]] opened in 2011, named \"Love Tilly Devine\" in honour of Devine.\n\nIn August 2011, Australia's [[Nine Network|Channel Nine]] commenced screening ''[[Underbelly: Razor]]'', a [[true crime]] television drama series that deals with the Leigh/Devine Sydney gangland wars in the 1930s. The series was based on the [[Ned Kelly Award]]-winning book by Larry Writer.<ref name=\"Writer\"/> Devine was portrayed by [[Chelsie Preston Crayford]], who was nominated for a [[Logie Awards of 2012|Logie Award]] for Most Popular New Female Talent.\n\n==See also==\n{{stack|}}\n*[[Kate Leigh]], Devine's bitter rival\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |first=George |last=Blaikie |title=Wild Women Of Sydney |publisher=Rigby Publishers |location=Australia |year=1980 |isbn=978-0-7270-1394-1 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |first1=E |last1=Butel |first2=T |last2=Thompson |title=Kings Cross Album |publisher=ATRAND Publishers |location=Australia |year=1984 |isbn=978-0-908272-06-8 |ref=}}\n*{{cite book |first1=Peter |last=Doyle |title=Crooks Like Us |publisher=Historic Houses Trust |location=Australia |year=2009 |isbn=978-1-876991-34-0 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |first=David |last=Hickie |title=Chow Hayes - Gunman |publisher=Collins/Angus & Robertson Publishers |location=Australia |year=1990 |isbn=978-0-207-16012-7 |ref=}}\n*{{cite book |first1=Vince |last=Kelly |title=Rugged Angel. The Amazing Career of Policewoman Lillian Armfield |publisher=Angus & Robertson |location=Australia |year=1961 |ref=}}\n*{{cite book |title=Kings Cross. 1936-1946 |publisher=Kings Cross Community Aid & Information Service |location=Sydney, Australia |year=1981 |isbn=0 9594116 0 7 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |first1=N|last1=Lipson |first2=T |last2=Barnao |title=As Crime Goes By |publisher=Ironbark Press |location=Australia |year=1992 |isbn=978-1-875471-14-0 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |first1=J |last1=Morton |first2=S |last2=Lobez |title=Gangland Australia |publisher=Melbourne University Press |location=Australia |year=2007 |isbn=978-0-522-85273-8 |ref=}}\n*{{cite book |first=Larry |last=Writer |title=Razor: A true story of slashers, gangsters, prostitutes and sly grog|publisher=Pan Macmillan |location=Australia |year=2001 |isbn=0 7329 1074 9 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |author1=Writer, Larry |title=Razor: Tilly Devine, Kate Leigh and the razor gangs |date=2009 |publisher=Macmillan Australia |edition=New |isbn=978-1-4050-3951-2 |ref={{harvid|Writer|2009}} }}\n*{{cite book |first1=Larry |last=Writer |title=Bumper: the life & times of Frank 'Bumper' Farrell |publisher=Hachette Australia |location=Australia |year=2011 |isbn=978-0-7336-2489-6 |ref= }}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A080318b.htm Tilly Devine profile], Australian Dictionary of Biography online edition; retrieved 9 March 2008.\n* [http://www.awm.gov.au/fiftyaustralians/15.asp Tilly Devine profile], awm.gov.au; retrieved 9 March 2008.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110311022057/http://www.timeoutsydney.com.au/thebridge/colourfulsydneyidentity/tilly-devine.aspx Tilly Devine biodata], timeoutsydney.com.au; retrieved 10 March 2010. \n* [http://oa.anu.edu.au/obituary/devine-matilda-mary-tilly-5970 Devine, Matilda Mary (Tilly; 1900\u20131970)], ''Daily Mirror'' obituary, page 9, 24 November 1970; retrieved 28 August 2011.\n* [http://oa.anu.edu.au/obituary/devine-matilda-mary-tilly-5970/text24400 Devine, Matilda Mary (Tilly; 1900\u20131970)], Obituary by Ron Saw from the ''Daily Telegraph'', page 6, 25 November 1970; retrieved 28 August 2011.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Devine, Tilly}}\n[[Category:1900 births]]\n[[Category:1970 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian criminals]]\n[[Category:Australian brothel owners and madams]]\n[[Category:Australian Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Criminals from Sydney]]\n[[Category:English emigrants to Australia]]\n[[Category:Organised crime in Australia]]\n[[Category:People from Camberwell]]\n[[Category:Female organized crime figures]]\n[[Category:Australian organised crime figures]]\n[[Category:Mob bosses]]\n[[Category:People associated with Kings Cross, New South Wales]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Australian criminal}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2011}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox person \n| name =Tilly Devine \n| image = Tilly Devine 1925.jpg\n| image_upright = 1.6\n| alt = \n| caption = Tilly Devine in 1925 \n| birth_name =Matilda Mary Twiss \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1900|09|30|df=y}} \n| birth_place = [[Camberwell]], [[London]] \n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1970|11|24|1900|09|30|df=y}}  \n| death_place = [[Concord Repatriation General Hospital|Concord Repatriation Hospital]], Sydney\n| burial_place = [[Eastern Suburbs Memorial Park]] \n| nationality = [[English Australian]] \n| other_names = ''Queen of Woolloomooloo''<ref name=smh-obit/> \n| occupation = \n| years_active = ''[[circa]]'' 1920s{{spaced endash}} 1950s \n| known_for = [[Razor gang]]s, [[Madam#Alternate use|madam]], [[sly-grog shop|sly-grog]] supply \n| notable_works =\n| criminal_charge    =  <!-- Criminality parameters should be supported with citations from reliable sources -->\n| criminal_penalty   = \n| criminal_status    =  \n| spouse             = {{plainlist|\n*James Edward \"Jim\" Devine {{small|(m. 1917, div. 1944)}}\n*Eric John Parsons {{small|(m. 1945, dec'd. 1958)}} }}\n}}\n'''Matilda Mary Devine''' (n\u00e9e '''Twiss''', 8 September 1900{{spaced ndash}}24 November 1970), known as '''Tilly Devine''', was an [[English Australian]] organised crime boss. She was involved in a wide range of activities, including [[sly-grog shop|sly-grog]], [[razor gang]]s, and prostitution, and became a famous folk figure in Sydney during the interwar years.\n\n==Early life==\nDevine was born the daughter of bricklayer Edward Twiss, and Alice Twiss (n\u00e9e Tubb) at 57 Hollington Street, [[Camberwell]], London in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{harvnb|Writer|2001|p=23}}</ref><ref>Census 1901, Camberwell, St George, District 5, page 12</ref> At 16 she married an Australian serviceman, '''James (Jim) Edward Devine''', (born  [[Brunswick, Victoria]], 1892, died [[Melbourne]], 1966), on 12 April 1917 at the Sacred Heart Church, Camberwell, London. The couple had one son, born at Camberwell in 1919.\n\nHer career in prostitution began when she was a teenager and continued after she was married. She and many English women were usually found soliciting on the wide footpaths on The Strand, at night. From 1915 onwards to 1919, she spent time at Bow Street Court and Lock Up for prostitution, theft and assault.\n\nWhen Jim returned to Australia she followed him back on the bride ship ''Waimana'', arriving in Sydney on 13 January 1920. Her son stayed in London and was brought up by her parents.<ref name= bio>{{cite book |first1=Judith |last1=Allen |first2=Baiba |last2=Irving |title= Devine, Matilda (Mary) (1900 - 1970) |work=[[Australian Dictionary of Biography]] |chapter-url= http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A080318b.htm |publisher=Australian National University |year=2011 |accessdate= 9 March 2008|chapter=Devine, Matilda Mary (Tilly) (1900\u20131970) }}</ref>  Both Tilly and Jim Devine rapidly became prominent illegal narcotics dealers, brothel owners and crime gangs members in the Sydney criminal milieu.\n\n==Criminal career==\n\nDevine became infamous in Sydney, initially as a prostitute, then later as a brothel madam and organised crime entrepreneur. The NSW Vagrancy Act 1905 prohibited men from running brothels; it did nothing to stop women with criminal gangs' support and bribes to the police from running criminal enterprises. Historian Larry Writer has noted that the Devines ran diversified operations. Elite \"call girls\" were available for politicians, businessmen and overseas guests of significance, while \"tenement girls\" were young working class women who resorted to casual prostitution to supplement their drug spendings, clothings and meagre earnings during times of Australian criminal and narcotic culture, absence of a comprehensive welfare state and unemployment. Older female prostitutes, \"boat girls\", catered to itinerant sailors or working class-men. Devine does not seem to have run similar operations for the gay sex market during this time because she believed it was not right.<ref>{{harvnb|Writer|2009|p=200}}</ref>\n\nDevine's wealth was legendary, although it was all earned from crime. She owned much real estate in Sydney, many luxury cars, looted gold and diamond jewellery and travelled by ship in first class staterooms. Much of her wealth was also used to pay bribes to the police sectors, and fines for her criminal convictions that spanned fifty years. Devine faced numerous court summons and was convicted on 204 occasions during her long criminal career, and served many gaol sentences in New South Wales gaols, mainly for prostitution, violent assault, affray and attempted murder. She was known to the police to be of a violent nature and was known to use firearms.\n\n==Marriage to Jim Devine ==\n[[File:James Devine 1939.jpg|thumb|Jim Devine in 1939]]\nJim Devine was an ex-serviceman and shearer, who was a violent 'stand-over' man, a convicted thief, a pimp, drug dealer, vicious thug and gunman. He was also an alcoholic. Devine committed a number of high-profile murders in Sydney between 1929 and 1931: notably, the murder of criminal George Leonard \"Gregory\" Gaffney on 17 July 1929,<ref>{{cite news |work=Sydney Morning Herald |title=Funeral Notice. George Leonard Gaffney|date=20 July 1929 |page=13 }}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Doyle|2009|p=237}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |work=Sydney Morning Herald |title=GANG WAR. GUN DUEL AT MAROUBRA. Man Fatally Shot., Others Wounded|date=19 July 1929 |page=13 }}</ref> secondly, as an accessory to the murder of [[Barney Dalton]] <ref>{{cite news |work=Sydney Morning Herald |title=Death Notice|date=12 November 1929 |first=Barney |last=Dalton |page=10 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |work=Sydney Morning Herald |title=Man Shot Dead. Underworld Warfare|date=11 November 1929 |page=11 }}</ref> on 9 November 1929 (with infamous Sydney gangster and assassin, Francis Donald \"Frankie\" Green) and, thirdly, the accidental shooting of taxi driver, Frederick Herbert Moffitt on 16 June 1931.<ref>{{cite news |work=Sydney Morning Herald |title=MAROUBRA MURDER. James Devine Charged. Counsel's Protest in Court|date=19 June 1931 |page=14 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |work=Sydney Morning Herald |title=Funeral Notice. Frederick Herbert Moffitt |date=18 June 1931 |page=7 }}</ref> Although he was charged with murder on more than one occasion, he was always acquitted, successfully arguing [[Self-defence (Australia)|self defence]]. He shot and killed Gaffney and Moffitt outside his and Tilly's [[Maroubra, New South Wales|Maroubra]] residence.<ref>{{harvnb|Blaikie|1980|p= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |work=Sydney Morning Herald |title=DEVINE Acquitted on murder charge. MAROUBRA SHOOTING|date=14 September 1929 |page=14 }}</ref>\n\nTilly and Jim Devine's marriage was marred by domestic violence. On 9 January 1931, Jim was charged at Central Police Court with the attempted murder of his wife after a heated argument at their Maroubra home. As Tilly ran out of the house, Jim fired a number of shots at her in a similar way to the murder of George Leonard Gaffney in 1929. Tilly escaped unscathed, the only damage being one of her brand new stilettos - the left one. Their terrified neighbours called the police resulting in Jim being arrested and charged over the incident. He was later acquitted, on 16 January 1931, because Tilly refused to testify.<ref>{{cite news |work=Sydney Morning Herald |title='HUSBAND CHARGED'. 'Alleged Attempted Murder|date=10 January 1931 |page=8 }}</ref> The Devines separated in the early 1940s and were finally divorced in January 1944.<ref>{{cite news |work=Sydney Morning Herald |title=Devine divorce hearing|date=31 March 1943 |page=11 }}</ref> Shortly after Tilly separated from Jim, long time criminal associate, Donald Alexander Kenney (1906-1963), known as 'Skinny Kenney', became Tilly's lover and stand-over man.<ref>{{cite news |work=The Wingham Chronicle And Manning River Observer |title=Skinny Kenny |date=5 October 1943}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Skinny Kenny |work=Truth |location=Sydney |date=5 July 1942 |page=17 }}</ref>\n\n==Second marriage==\n\nDevine married for the second time on 19 May 1945 to ex-seaman and returned serviceman '''Eric John Parsons''' (born [[Melbourne]] 1901, died [[Sydney]] 1958).<ref>{{cite news |work=Sydney Morning Herald |title=Death Notice: Eric John Parsons |date=24 November 1958 }}</ref>\n\nTilly famously shot Parsons in the leg after an argument only months before they were married. This shooting occurred at her other Sydney residence: 191 Palmer Street, [[Darlinghurst]]. The house was almost opposite the notorious ''Tradesman's Arms Hotel''. It was at this hotel that Devine met Eric Parsons.<ref>{{cite news |work=Sydney Morning Herald |date=21 February 1945 |page=5 |title=Tilly Devine Charged. Shooting Alleged }}</ref> She was arrested by police and charged with the shooting,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article2617043 |work=[[The Canberra Times]] |title=Tilly Devine On Attempted Murder Charge in Sydney |page=3 |date=21 February 1945 |publisher=National Library of Australia |accessdate=28 August 2011}}</ref> but was acquitted at trial on 31 March 1945.<ref>{{cite news |work=Sydney Morning Herald |date=30 March 1945 |page=4 |title=Tilly Devine Discharged }}</ref> They were happily married for 13 years until Eric Parsons died of cancer on 22 November 1958.\n\nFor over 30 years, Devine lived at 335 Malabar Road, [[Maroubra, New South Wales|Maroubra]] in Sydney's south-eastern suburbs. A number of homicides were committed at this residence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article22903708|title=Guns Blazed in Sydney's Underworld!|date=8 July 1950|pages=26|accessdate=5 November 2017|via=Trove}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |work=Sydney Morning Herald |date=11 July 1931  |title=Desperate Gun Duel. \"Divine's Alleged Confession at Moffitt Inquest\" |page=11 |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article16792668 |publisher=National Library of Australia }}</ref> The property remained derelict from the 1950s onwards. It was sold in 2009 and the new owner built a new house on the lot.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/wreckers-ball-for-notorious-brothelkeepers-home-20090717-do93.html|title=Wrecker's ball for notorious brothel-keeper's home|first=Clancy|last=Yeates|date=18 July 2009|accessdate=5 November 2017|via=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref>\n\n==Decline and death==\nAlthough Devine had been one of Sydney's wealthiest women, by 1955 the Taxation Department ordered her to pay more than \u00a320,000 in unpaid income tax and fines sending her close to bankruptcy.<ref>{{cite news |work=[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]] |location=Melbourne |title=Tilly in 'Ton of Trouble' |date=18 October 1955 |page=5 }}</ref> In 1953 Devine boasted to the media, \"I am a lucky, lucky girl. I have more diamonds than the Queen of England's stowaways - and better ones too!\"<ref>{{harvnb|Blaikie|1980|page=124}}</ref> She sold off her last brothel in Palmer Street, Darlinghurst in 1968, and died two years later.<ref name=\"Writer\">{{harvnb|Writer|2001|p= }}</ref>\n\nDevine was famous for flamboyant acts of generosity, and also for her violent feud with criminal vice rival [[Kate Leigh]]. Devine was charged by the famous Sydney Detective [[Frank Farrell (rugby league)|Frank Farrell]] on many occasions, and their feud lasted for 30 years.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}}\n\nDevine had suffered from chronic bronchitis for 20 years, and died of cancer, aged 70 at the [[Concord Repatriation General Hospital|Concord Repatriation Hospital]] in Sydney on 24 November 1970. Her funeral service was held at the Sacred Heart Catholic Church, Darlinghurst.<ref name=smh-obit>{{cite web|title=Devine, Matilda Mary (Tilly) (1900\u20131970): Obituary|url=http://oa.anu.edu.au/obituary/devine-matilda-mary-tilly-5970/text24395|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=28 August 2011|page=18|date=25 November 1970|via=Obituaries Australia http://oa.anu.edu.au/obituary/devine-matilda-mary-tilly-5970/text24395}}</ref> She was cremated at Botany Crematorium, now known as [[Eastern Suburbs Memorial Park]], on 26 November 1970 with Catholic rites by her married name, Matilda Mary Parsons. She was survived by her son Frederick Ralph (Devine) Twiss (1919\u20131978) and 2 grandchildren.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}} Her funeral service was poorly attended and her death went virtually unnoticed by Sydney's media and population and it was said that very few people openly mourned her death. The only public eulogy offered to Devine was given by the then police commissioner Norman Allan who said: \"She was a villain, but who am I to judge her?\"<ref>{{harvnb|Lipson|Barnao|1992|p=135}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n[[Peter Kenna]] wrote a play called ''The Slaughter of St Teresa\u2019s Day'' (1973 Currency Press),<ref name= slaughter>{{cite web |title=  Fifty Australians - Tilly Devine |publisher= Australian War Memorial |url= http://www.awm.gov.au/fiftyaustralians/15.asp |accessdate= 9 March 2008}}</ref> based on Devine's life.\n\nThe song \"Miss Divine\" from the 1990 [[Icehouse (band)|Icehouse]] album ''[[Code Blue (Icehouse album)|Code Blue]]'' is about Devine.\n\nA popular cafe-nightclub in [[Lyneham, Australian Capital Territory|Lyneham]], [[Canberra]] is called [[Tilley's Devine Cafe|Tilleys Devine Cafe Gallery]]. A wine bar in [[Darlinghurst, New South Wales|Darlinghurst]], [[Sydney]] opened in 2011, named \"Love Tilly Devine\" in honour of Devine.\n\nIn August 2011, Australia's [[Nine Network|Channel Nine]] commenced screening ''[[Underbelly: Razor]]'', a [[true crime]] television drama series that deals with the Leigh/Devine Sydney gangland wars in the 1930s. The series was based on the [[Ned Kelly Award]]-winning book by Larry Writer.<ref name=\"Writer\"/> Devine was portrayed by [[Chelsie Preston Crayford]], who was nominated for a [[Logie Awards of 2012|Logie Award]] for Most Popular New Female Talent.\n\n==See also==\n{{stack|}}\n*[[Kate Leigh]], Devine's bitter rival\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |first=George |last=Blaikie |title=Wild Women Of Sydney |publisher=Rigby Publishers |location=Australia |year=1980 |isbn=978-0-7270-1394-1 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |first1=E |last1=Butel |first2=T |last2=Thompson |title=Kings Cross Album |publisher=ATRAND Publishers |location=Australia |year=1984 |isbn=978-0-908272-06-8 |ref=}}\n*{{cite book |first1=Peter |last=Doyle |title=Crooks Like Us |publisher=Historic Houses Trust |location=Australia |year=2009 |isbn=978-1-876991-34-0 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |first=David |last=Hickie |title=Chow Hayes - Gunman |publisher=Collins/Angus & Robertson Publishers |location=Australia |year=1990 |isbn=978-0-207-16012-7 |ref=}}\n*{{cite book |first1=Vince |last=Kelly |title=Rugged Angel. The Amazing Career of Policewoman Lillian Armfield |publisher=Angus & Robertson |location=Australia |year=1961 |ref=}}\n*{{cite book |title=Kings Cross. 1936-1946 |publisher=Kings Cross Community Aid & Information Service |location=Sydney, Australia |year=1981 |isbn=0 9594116 0 7 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |first1=N|last1=Lipson |first2=T |last2=Barnao |title=As Crime Goes By |publisher=Ironbark Press |location=Australia |year=1992 |isbn=978-1-875471-14-0 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |first1=J |last1=Morton |first2=S |last2=Lobez |title=Gangland Australia |publisher=Melbourne University Press |location=Australia |year=2007 |isbn=978-0-522-85273-8 |ref=}}\n*{{cite book |first=Larry |last=Writer |title=Razor: A true story of slashers, gangsters, prostitutes and sly grog|publisher=Pan Macmillan |location=Australia |year=2001 |isbn=0 7329 1074 9 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |author1=Writer, Larry |title=Razor: Tilly Devine, Kate Leigh and the razor gangs |date=2009 |publisher=Macmillan Australia |edition=New |isbn=978-1-4050-3951-2 |ref={{harvid|Writer|2009}} }}\n*{{cite book 